{"title_page": "Frank T. Cary", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name  = Frank T. Cary\n| birth_name = Frank Taylor Cary\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1920|12|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Gooding, Idaho]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2006|01|01|1920|12|14}}\n| death_place = [[Darien, Connecticut]]\n| nationality  = [[United States|American]]\n| occupation  = \n| alma mater = {{unbulleted list |[[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[Bachelor's degree]])|[[Stanford Graduate School of Business]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])}}\n| known for = Former Chairmain and CEO of [[IBM]]\n}}\n\n'''Frank T. Cary''' (December 14, 1920 \u2013 January 1, 2006) was an [[United States of America|American]] executive and businessman. Cary served as the [[Chairman]] of [[IBM]] from 1973 to 1983 and [[CEO]] from 1973 to 1981.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nFrank Taylor Cary was born on December 14, 1920, in [[Gooding, Idaho]]<ref name=mit>{{citeweb|url=http://news.mit.edu/2006/obit-cary|title=Frank Cary, life member of Corporation, dies|website=mit.edu|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>, the son of Dr. Frank T. Cary and Ida Hayden.<ref name=nytimes>{{citeweb|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/frank-cary-past-chairman-of-ibm-is-dead-at-85.html|title=Frank Cary, Past Chairman of I.B.M., Is Dead at 85|date=Jan 6, 2006|website=nytimes.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> After a short period of his birth, the family moved to [[Inglewood, California]].<ref name=nytimes>{{citeweb|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/frank-cary-past-chairman-of-ibm-is-dead-at-85.html|title=Frank Cary, Past Chairman of I.B.M., Is Dead at 85|date=Jan 6, 2006|website=nytimes.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> He earned a bachelor's degree from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1943, then in 1948 earned his M.B.A. from [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]]<ref name=mit/><ref name=ibmbio/>\n\n==Career==\n===IBM===\nCary joined IBM in 1948 as a salesman in Los Angeles.<ref name=mit /> He held a variety of management positions and became president of the Data Processing Division in 1964.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PTfYYJLFB20C&pg=PA2&dq=Computerworld,+March+10,+1980+frank+t+cary&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjb75fK7sXmAhXQVc0KHd1pBj8Q6AEwAXoECAcQAQ Computerworld], March 10, 1980</ref> Advancing through the management ranks, he became general manager of data processing and vice president after two years, then became a senior vice president in 1967, in the following year, he was appointed as member of the board of directors, then joined the Corporate Office and the Management Review Committee.<ref name=ibmbio>{{citeweb|url=https://www.ibm.com/ibm/history/exhibits/chairmen/chairmen_6.html|title=Frank T. Cary|website=ibm.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In January 1973, Cary was named Chairman and CEO.\n\nDuring his tenure as chief executive at IBM, he presided over a period of rapid growth in product, revenue and profit. His most notable accomplishment was recognizing that the [[personal computer]] was going to be an emerging product category that could ultimately be a threat to IBM. Consequently, he forced the creation of a special, small dedicated group to spearhead an answer to [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], within IBM but totally protected from the internal bureaucracy of a large corporation.\n\nHe stepped down from his position in 1981, remained a director until 1991.<ref name=ibmbio />\n===Boards and Committees===\nCary was Chairman of biotechnology company [[Celgene Corporation]] from 1986 to 1990.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2006/01/08/frank_cary_85_led_ibm_through_1970s/|title=Frank Cary, 85; led IBM through 1970s|date=January 8, 2006|website=boston.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> He was a member of the Steering Committee of the [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |title=Former Steering Committee Members |work=bilderbergmeetings.org |publisher=[[Bilderberg Group]] |accessdate=February 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |archivedate=June 30, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nHe joined the MIT Corporation in 1974, and became a life member in 1984. He served on several committees, including the committee of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science.<ref name=mit />\n\nHe served on the board of directors of [[JP Morgan]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[Texaco]], and others. He also served on boards of many nonprofit organizations, including the [[American Museum of Natural History]] and [[Rockefeller University]].<ref name=mit />\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nHe was married to Anne (Curtis) Cary. They raised two sons, and a daughter.<ref name=mit /> His hobbies included skiing, tennis, and golf.<ref name=latimes>{{citeweb|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-jan-05-me-cary5-story.html|title=Frank Cary, 67; IBM Head Instrumental in Push to Develop PCs|date=January 5, 2006|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> He died at the age of 85, at his home in [[Darien, Connecticut]], on [[New Year's Day]] 2006.<ref name=nytimes />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www-03.ibm.com/ibm/history/exhibits/chairmen/chairmen_6.html Official Biography on IBM website]\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box|title=[[IBM|CEOs of IBM]]|\n                 before=[[T. Vincent Learson]]|\n                 after=[[John Opel|John R. Opel]]|\n                 years=1973\u20131981}}\n{{end box}}\n{{IBM}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cary, Frank T.}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Gooding, Idaho]]\n[[Category:IBM employees]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:People from Darien, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of Fortune 500 companies]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name  = Frank T. Cary\n| birth_name = Frank Taylor Cary\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1920|12|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Gooding, Idaho]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2006|01|01|1920|12|14}}\n| death_place = [[Darien, Connecticut]]\n| nationality  = [[United States|American]]\n| occupation  = \n| alma mater = {{unbulleted list |[[University of California, Los Angeles]] ([[Bachelor's degree]])|[[Stanford Graduate School of Business]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])}}\n| known for = Former Chairmain and CEO of [[IBM]]\n}}\n\n'''Frank T. Cary''' (December 14, 1920 \u2013 January 1, 2006) was an [[United States of America|American]] executive and businessman. Cary served as the [[Chairman]] of [[IBM]] from 1973 to 1983 and [[CEO]] from 1973 to 1981.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nFrank Taylor Cary was born on December 14, 1920, in [[Gooding, Idaho]]<ref name=mit>{{citeweb|url=http://news.mit.edu/2006/obit-cary|title=Frank Cary, life member of Corporation, dies|website=mit.edu|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>, the son of Dr. Frank T. Cary and Ida Hayden.<ref name=nytimes>{{citeweb|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/frank-cary-past-chairman-of-ibm-is-dead-at-85.html|title=Frank Cary, Past Chairman of I.B.M., Is Dead at 85|date=Jan 6, 2006|website=nytimes.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> After a short period of his birth, the family moved to [[Inglewood, California]].<ref name=nytimes>{{citeweb|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/frank-cary-past-chairman-of-ibm-is-dead-at-85.html|title=Frank Cary, Past Chairman of I.B.M., Is Dead at 85|date=Jan 6, 2006|website=nytimes.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> He earned a bachelor's degree from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] in 1943, then in 1948 earned his M.B.A. from [[Stanford Graduate School of Business]]<ref name=mit/><ref name=ibmbio/>\n\n==Career==\n===IBM===\nCary joined IBM in 1948 as a salesman in Los Angeles.<ref name=mit /> He held a variety of management positions and became president of the Data Processing Division in 1964.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PTfYYJLFB20C&pg=PA2&dq=Computerworld,+March+10,+1980+frank+t+cary&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjb75fK7sXmAhXQVc0KHd1pBj8Q6AEwAXoECAcQAQ Computerworld], March 10, 1980</ref> Advancing through the management ranks, he became general manager of data processing and vice president after two years, then became a senior vice president in 1967, in the following year, he was appointed as member of the board of directors, then joined the Corporate Office and the Management Review Committee.<ref name=ibmbio>{{citeweb|url=https://www.ibm.com/ibm/history/exhibits/chairmen/chairmen_6.html|title=Frank T. Cary|website=ibm.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In January 1973, Cary was named Chairman and CEO.\n\nDuring his tenure as chief executive at IBM, he presided over a period of rapid growth in product, revenue and profit. His most notable accomplishment was recognizing that the [[personal computer]] was going to be an emerging product category that could ultimately be a threat to IBM. Consequently, he forced the creation of a special, small dedicated group to spearhead an answer to [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], within IBM but totally protected from the internal bureaucracy of a large corporation.\n\nHe stepped down from his position in 1981, remained a director until 1991.<ref name=ibmbio />\n===Boards and Committees===\nCary was Chairman of biotechnology company [[Celgene Corporation]] from 1986 to 1990.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/globe/obituaries/articles/2006/01/08/frank_cary_85_led_ibm_through_1970s/|title=Frank Cary, 85; led IBM through 1970s|date=January 8, 2006|website=boston.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> He was a member of the Steering Committee of the [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |title=Former Steering Committee Members |work=bilderbergmeetings.org |publisher=[[Bilderberg Group]] |accessdate=February 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |archivedate=June 30, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nHe joined the MIT Corporation in 1974, and became a life member in 1984. He served on several committees, including the committee of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science.<ref name=mit />\n\nHe served on the board of directors of [[JP Morgan]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[Texaco]], and others. He also served on boards of many nonprofit organizations, including the [[American Museum of Natural History]] and [[Rockefeller University]].<ref name=mit />\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nHe was married to Anne (Curtis) Cary. They raised two sons, and a daughter.<ref name=mit /> His hobbies included skiing, tennis, and golf<ref name=latimes>{{citeweb|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-jan-05-me-cary5-story.html|title=Frank Cary, 67; IBM Head Instrumental in Push to Develop PCs|date=January 5, 2006|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>. He died at the age of 85, at his home in [[Darien, Connecticut]], on [[New Year's Day]] 2006.<ref name=nytimes />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www-03.ibm.com/ibm/history/exhibits/chairmen/chairmen_6.html Official Biography on IBM website]\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box|title=[[IBM|CEOs of IBM]]|\n                 before=[[T. Vincent Learson]]|\n                 after=[[John Opel|John R. Opel]]|\n                 years=1973\u20131981}}\n{{end box}}\n{{IBM}}\n{{Auth