ofessor Matthew Norman\n* ''[[The Conspirators (1944 film)|The Conspirators]]'' (1944) as Casino Attendant (uncredited)\n* ''[[House of Frankenstein (1944 film)|House of Frankenstein]]'' (1944) as Ullman\n* ''[[The Big Bonanza]]'' (1944) as Dr. Ballou\n* ''[[The Jade Mask]]'' (1945) as Harper\n* ''[[Hotel Berlin]]'' (1945) as Fritz (uncredited)\n* ''[[A Medal for Benny]]'' (1945) as Father Bly (uncredited)\n* ''[[Blonde Ransom]]'' (1945) as Judge\n* ''[[Rhapsody in Blue (film)|Rhapsody in Blue]]'' (1945) as Guest (uncredited)\n* ''[[Voice of the Whistler]]'' (1945) as Dr. Rose (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Tiger Woman (1945 film)|The Tiger Woman]]'' (1945) as Coroner\n* ''[[The Strange Mr. Gregory]]'' (1945) as Riker, the Butler\n* ''[[A Guy Could Change]]'' (1946) as Doctor (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Shadow Returns]]'' (1946) as Michael Hasdon\n* ''[[Song of Arizona]]'' (1946) as Doctor (uncredited)\n* ''[[My Pal Trigger]]'' (1946) as Judge J.E. Ellis (uncredited)\n* ''[[Sister Kenny]]'' (1946) as Dr. Chuter (uncredited)\n* ''[[Home in Oklahoma]]'' (1946) as Jason Cragmyle\n* ''[[Mr. District Attorney (1947 film)|Mr. District Attorney]]'' (1947) as Peter Lantz (uncredited)\n* ''[[Yankee Fakir]]'' (1947) as Banker H.W. Randall\n* ''[[Monsieur Verdoux]]'' (1947) as Doctor (uncredited)\n* ''[[Violence (film)|Violence]]'' (1947) as Pop\n* ''[[The Secret Life of Walter Mitty (1947 film)|The Secret Life of Walter Mitty]]'' (1947) as Karl Maasdam\n* ''[[Song of Love (1947 film)|Song of Love]]'' (1947) as Mr. Fuerbach (uncredited)\n* ''[[Escape Me Never (1947 film)|Escape Me Never]]'' (1947) as The Minister\n* ''[[Joe Palooka in Fighting Mad]]'' (1948) as Dr. MacKenzie\n* ''[[Carson City Raiders]]'' (1948) as Razor the Barber\n* ''[[I, Jane Doe]]'' (1948) as Doctor (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Gallant Blade]]'' (1948) as Major (uncredited)\n* ''[[Barbary Pirate (film)|Barbary Pirate]]'' (1949) as Cathcart\n* ''[[Samson and Delilah (1949 film)|Samson and Delilah]]'' (1949) as Village Barber\n* ''[[The Arizona Cowboy]]'' (1950) as Major Sheridan\n* ''[[Cargo to Capetown]]'' (1950) as Judge Van Meeger (uncredited)\n* ''[[Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye (film)|Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye]]'' (1950) as 'Doc' Darius Green\n* ''The Lady and the Bandit'' (1951) as Count Eckhardt\n* ''[[Superman and the Mole Men]]'' (1951) as Hospital Superintendent (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Director===\n* ''[[The Secret Sin]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[The Case of Becky (1915 film)|The Case of Becky]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[Alien Souls]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[The Storm (1916 film)|The Storm]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[Public Opinion (1916 film)|Public Opinion]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[Lost and Won (1917 film)|Lost and Won]]'' ([[1917 in film|1917]])\n* ''[[Castles for Two]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[An American Widow]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[The Claim (1918 film)|The Claim]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[Treasure of the Sea]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[Behind Masks]]'' (1921)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Frank Reicher}}\n* {{IMDb name|0717046}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Find a Grave|5272}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reicher, Frank}}\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:German male stage actors]]\n[[Category:German male film actors]]\n[[Category:German male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:German film directors]]\n[[Category:German film producers]]\n[[Category:People from Munich]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male actors]]\n[[Category:RKO Pictures contract players]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Reicher"}
{"title_page": "Melanie Phillips", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = File:Melanie Phillips.jpg\n| caption     = Phillips in 2014\n| name        = Melanie Phillips\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1951|6|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = {{Hlist | Journalist | Author | Publisher }}\n| title       = \n| family      =\n| spouse      = [[Joshua Rozenberg]]\n| children    = \n| relatives   = \n| ethnicity   = \n| religion    = \n| alma_mater  = [[St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| credits     = {{Unbulleted list|item_style=white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 0.3em | ''[[The Times]]'' columnist | Former columnist for <br />  ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Spectator]]''<br>and the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' |  | Author of ''[[Londonistan (book)|Londonistan]]'' }}\n| URL         = \n}}\n'''Melanie Phillips''' (born 4 June 1951) is a British journalist, author, and public commentator. She began her career writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''[[New Statesman]]''. During the 1990s, she came to identify with ideas more associated with the right and currently writes for ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', and ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'', covering political and social issues from a [[Social conservatism|social conservative]] perspective. Phillips, quoting [[Irving Kristol]], defines herself as a [[classical liberalism|liberal]] who has \"been mugged by reality\".<ref name=\"Beckett\">Andy Beckett [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/mar/07/dailymail.pressandpublishing/print \"The changing face of Melanie Phillips\"], ''The Guardian'', 7 March 2003.</ref>\n\nPhillips has appeared as a panellist on the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[The Moral Maze]]'' and [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]''. She was awarded the [[Orwell Prize#Journalism category|Orwell Prize for Journalism]] in 1996, while she was writing for ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref name=\"OP profile\">{{cite web | url= http://theorwellprize.co.uk/shortlists/melanie-phillips/| title= Orwell Prize Melanie Phillips \u2013 Columnist, Daily Mail|date=|accessdate=25 November 2011| work=The Orwell Prize}}</ref> Her books include the memoir ''Guardian Angel: My Story, My Britain''.<ref>{{cite news| first=Gaby | last=Hinsliff | url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/17/guardian-angel-melanie-phillips-review#start-of-comments | title=Guardian Angel: My Story, My Britain by Melanie Phillips \u2013 review | work=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 May 2013|accessdate=25 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMelanie Phillips was born in [[Hammersmith]], the daughter of Mabel (n\u00e9e Cohen) and Alfred Phillips.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=aZJuIULum%2Fwl2BcBJsB4SA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=22 June 2017|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> Her family is Jewish and emigrated to Britain from Poland and Russia.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2319192/Why-Left-hates-families-MELANIE-PHIILLIPS-reveals-selfish-sneers-Guardianistas-Left-actively-fosters--revels--family-breakdown-.html Why the Left hates families: Melanie Phillips reveals how the selfish sneers of Guardianistas made her see how the Left actively fosters \u2013 and revels in \u2013 family breakdown...], ''[[Daily Mail]]'', 3 May 2013</ref> According to her account, the name \"Phillips\" was imposed by British officials who were unable to pronounce her family's Polish name. She describes her family as \"poor\" people living as outsiders in an impoverished area of London, who \"kept their heads down and tried to assimilate\".<ref name=\"auto1\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2320940/MELANIE-PHILLIPS-Too-immigrants-today-expect-Britain-adopt-THEIR-culture.html Daily Mail article]</ref> Her father, Alfred, was a dress salesman, while her mother, Mabel, ran a children's clothes shop and both were committed [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] voters.<ref name=\"Beckett\"/>  She has stated that her father was \"gentle, kind and innocent\", an \"overgrown child\", and that \"as my other parent he just wasn\u2019t there\", which taught her \"how the absence of proper fathering could screw up a child for life\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> She was educated at [[Putney High School]], a girls' fee-paying [[independent school]] in [[Putney]], London. Later she read English at [[St Anne's College, Oxford]].<ref>The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History, ed. William D. Rubinstein, et. al., Palgrave Macmillan, 2011, p. 753</ref>\n\n==Journalism career==\nPhillips trained as a journalist on the ''Evening Echo'', a local newspaper in [[Hemel Hempstead]],<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> as her probationary period in the provinces, then compulsory for the profession. After winning the Young Journalist of the Year award in 1976,<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> she spent a short period at the ''[[New Society (magazine)|New Society]]'' magazine.\n\nShe joined ''The Guardian'' newspaper in 1977, becoming its social services correspondent and social policy leader writer. In 1984, she became the paper's news editor,<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> and was reported to have fainted on her first day.<ref name=\"Hillmore\">Peter Hillmore [http://www.newstatesman.com/200303100018 \"NS Profile - Melanie Phillips\"], ''New Statesman'', 10 March 2003</ref> In 1982, she defended the Labour Party at the time of the split with the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]]. Her opinion column began in 1987. While working for ''The Guardian'', Phillips was persuaded to write a play called ''Traitors'' by [[Julia Pascal]], who directed it.<ref name=\"Phillips2017\">{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/words-i-thought-id-never-write-im-a-novelist-kdnjlvqc0|title=Words I thought I'd never write: I'm a novelist|work=The Times|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref> It was performed at [[the Drill Hall]] from January 1986. The play was set at the time of the [[1982 Lebanon War]] and centred around the moral dilemmas of a Jewish journalist who as political editor of a liberal magazine has to decide whether to veto an article written in anti-semitic tones, and also whether she is right to publish a leaked document about the [[Falklands War]]. The play was reviewed by [[John Peter (critic)|John Peter]] in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' as \"a play of blistering intelligence and fearless moral questioning\", although he considered it bordering on implausible.<ref>[[John Peter (critic)|John Peter]]. \"Amoral acquiescence\". ''The Sunday Times''. 26 January 1986.</ref> According to Phillips, writing in December 2017, it was the only positive review the play received.<ref name=\"Phillips2017\"/> Phillips left ''The Guardian'' in 1993, saying that her relationship with the paper and its readers had become \"like a really horrific family argument\",<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> and that she had seen the \"reality\" that \"the west ha[d] lost its moral compass\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She took her opinion column to ''The Guardian''{{'s}} sister-paper ''[[The Observer]]'', then to ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' in 1998,<ref name=\"Hillmore\"/> before beginning her association with the tabloid ''[[Daily Mail]]'' in 2001. She also writes for ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'', ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' and other periodicals. \n\nIn November 2010, ''The Spectator'' and Phillips apologised and agreed to pay substantial compensation and legal costs to a prominent British Muslim they falsely accused of antisemitism.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/25/spectator-apology-muslim-antisemitism|title=The Spectator apologises for falsely accusing Muslim of antisemitism|last=Halliday|first=Josh|date=25 November 2010|accessdate=27 September 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The following year, she resigned from the magazine after it apologised and paid compensation for another of her pieces which, it said, contained an allegation that was \"completely false\".<ref name=guardian1>{{cite news | url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2011/jun/28/the-spectator-blogging | title=Why Melanie Phillips quit The Spectator|date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=4 May 2013| work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Roy | last=Greenslade}}</ref>\n\nSince 2003, she has written a blog, once hosted by ''[[The Spectator]]'', but following her resignation from the magazine in June 2011,<ref name=guardian1 /><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2011/06/melanie-phillips-spectator | title=Goodbye, Melanie!|date=24 June 2011 |accessdate=4 May 2013| work=News Statesman (blog)}}</ref> it is hosted on her website.<ref>{{cite web|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|title=My blog's new home|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/melaniephillips/7029239/my-blogs-new-home.thtml|publisher=The Spectator|accessdate=17 December 2011|date=16 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507210447/http://www.spectator.co.uk/melaniephillips/7029239/my-blogs-new-home.thtml|archivedate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In September 2013, it emerged that her ''Mail'' column was to end, although according to Phillips, the newspaper wanted her to continue to write features and other articles for it.<ref>William Turvill [http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/melanie-phillips-bows-out-after-12-years-mail-columnist-dominic-lawson-tipped-replace-her \"Melanie Phillips bows out after 12 years as Mail columnist, Dominic Lawson tipped to replace her\"], ''Press Gazette'', 12 September 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she launched an [[e-book]] publishing company called emBooks, to promote her book, together with several others, and self-promotional merchandise to the US market.<ref name=\"embooks\">{{cite news| first=Charlie | last=Cooper | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/online/phillips-launches-brand-melanie-as-she-tries-to-become-the-darling-of-the-american-right-8604621.html | title=Phillips launches 'Brand Melanie' as she tries to become the darling of the American right | work=[[The Independent]] | date=5 May 2013 | accessdate=25 August 2013 | location=London}}</ref> She currently writes for ''[[The Times]]''.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/profile/melanie-phillips</ref>\n\nShe has a weekly radio show on [[Voice of Israel]], is a regular panellist on BBC Radio's ''[[The Moral Maze]]'' and appears frequently on BBC TV's signature political shows ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' and ''[[The Daily Politics]]''.\n\n==Views and opinions==\nThe BBC has said that Phillips \"is regarded as one of the [British] media's leading right-wing voices\" and a \"controversial\" columnist.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/programmes/question_time/6727447.stm List of Panelists] for [[Question Time (TV series)|''Question Time'']], BBC website, 6 June 2007.</ref> [[Nick Cohen]] wrote in 2011 that she has become [[Defamation|vilified]] by ''The Guardian''.<ref name=\"Cohen2011\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Nick|authorlink=Nick Cohen|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/nickcohen/7457633/a-regiment-of-women-monsterers.thtml|title=A regiment of women monsterers|work=[[The Spectator]]|date=6 December 2011|access-date=17 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111208022649/http://www.spectator.co.uk/nickcohen/7457633/a-regiment-of-women-monsterers.thtml|archive-date=8 December 2011}}</ref> Phillips herself stated in 2006, during an interview with [[Jackie Ashley]] for the newspaper, that it often misrepresents her opinions.<ref name=\"Ashley2006\"/>\n\n===International issues===\n\n====Islamophobia====\nPhillips was heavily criticised for an article she wrote in the Jewish Chronicle which suggested that \u201cthe taunt of Islamophobia is used to silence any criticism of the Islamic world, including Islamic extremism\u201d and \u201cfacilitates\u201d antisemitism. The editor of the Jewish Chronicle, while not offering regret for publishing the article, did acknowledge that the article had been divisive and apologised to readers who had been angered or upset by the piece. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/news/2019/dec/17/islamophobia-a-bogus-label-jewish-chronicle-under-fire-over-story</ref>\n\n====Iran====\nShe is a staunch critic of [[Iran]] and has written and spoken frequently about the threat she perceives it to be, particularly if it were to obtain nuclear weapons.<ref>{{cite news|first=Melanie | last=Phillips | url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/features/24356/hezbollah-cells-await-irans-orders/ | title=Hezbollah cells await Iran's orders | work=[[The Spectator]] | date=2 August 2006 | accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MPdailymail\">{{cite news|first=Melanie | last=Phillips | url=http://phillipsblog.dailymail.co.uk/2012/01/why-iran-will-not-come-to-its-senses.html | title=Why Iran will not 'come to its senses' | work=[[Mail Online]] | date=25 January 2012 | accessdate=21 June 2013 | location=London}}</ref> The Iranian regime, she writes, \"has seen itself at war with the west ever since it [[Iranian Revolution|came to power]] in 1979, and which has been involved in arguably every major terrorist atrocity against it\". In her view, Iran's leaders are \"religious fanatics\" who are \"impervious to reason\" and who \"would be happy\" to bring about an [[Islamic eschatology|apocalyptic]] [[End time|end of days]]. Thus, \"there is no alternative to force if it is to be stopped.\"<ref name=\"MPdailymail\" /> She has drawn criticism for her hard-line approach from various commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/oct/31/melanie-phillips-islamism-spectator|title=The personal jihad of Melanie Phillips|date=31 October 2009|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jun/18/melanie-phillips-rightwing|title=What drove Melanie Phillips to the right?|date=18 June 2010|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nShe has said that she supports a [[two-state solution]] in theory but that it cannot work in practice, commenting: \"I would have no problem with a Palestine that would live in peace alongside Israel ... I respond to the evidence of what is actually happening. Israel is being demonised ... If Israel were to leave the West Bank, it would turn Islamist overnight and become an Iranian proxy on Israel's doorstep. That is why I cannot support a state of Palestine.\"<ref name=fpm>{{cite news |url=http://www.frontpagemag.com/readArticle.aspx?ARTID=35689 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20170524222747/http://archive.frontpagemag.com/readArticle.aspx?ARTID=35689 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 May 2017 |publisher=[[FrontPage Magazine]] |date=24 July 2009 |title=Alan Dershowitz vs. Melanie Phillips |first=Jamie |last=Glazov |accessdate=2 August 2009  }}</ref>\n\nPhillips's criticisms of liberal Jews who disagree with her positions on Israel have been mocked or condemned by writers such as [[Alan Dershowitz]],<ref name=\"The Spectator 9 July 2009\">{{cite news |url= http://www.spectator.co.uk/2009/07/a-reply-to-melanie-phillips/|title= A reply to Melanie Phillips |last= Dershowitz | first = Alan|date= 9 July 2009|work= [[The Spectator]] |publisher= [[Press Holdings]]| accessdate= 10 May 2016 }}</ref> Rabbi David Goldberg,<ref>\"... it would have to be someone particularly dim who begins a conversation with me at one of those north London dinner parties where writers such as... Melanie Phillips... claim to have been shocked by the anti-semitic hostility of the chattering classes...\" in \"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jan/26/religion.uk1 Let's have a sense of proportion]\" by Rabbi David Goldberg, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 January 2002</ref> and [[Jonathan Freedland]] who criticised Phillips's labelling of [[Independent Jewish Voices]], a group of liberal Jews, as \"Jews For Genocide\". Freedland wrote in ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'': \"Now, as it happens, I have multiple criticisms of IJV ... but even their most trenchant opponents must surely blanch at the notion that these critics of Israel and of Anglo-Jewish officialdom are somehow in favour of genocide\u2014literally, eager to see the murder and eradication of the Jewish people ... it is an absurdity, one that drains the word 'genocide' of any meaning\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Freedland, Jonathan|url=http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=51460&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchstr=eager%20to%20see%20the%20murder%20and%20eradication%20of%20the%20Jewish%20people&srchtxt=0&srchhead=1&srchauthor=0&srchsandp=0&scsrch=0|title=The danger of Melanie Phillips|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=30 March 2007|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005065425/http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=51460&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchstr=eager%20to%20see%20the%20murder%20and%20eradication%20of%20the%20Jewish%20people&srchtxt=0&srchhead=1&srchauthor=0&srchsandp=0&scsrch=0|archivedate=5 October 2011|author-link = Jonathan Freedland}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nEarly in the presidency of [[Barack Obama]], Phillips accused him of \"adopting the agenda of the Islamist\" and of being \"firmly in the Islamists' camp\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/oct/31/melanie-phillips-islamism-spectator | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Ed | last=Husain | title=The personal jihad of Melanie Phillips | date=31 October 2009}}</ref> Shortly after Obama's re-election for a second term, Phillips said that \"Four years ago, America put into the White House a sulky narcissist with an unbroken history of involvement in thuggish, corrupt, far-left, black power, Jew-bashing, west-hating politics\". She warned that Obama would lead America into a \"terrifying darkness\". ''[[The Independent]]'' termed it \"rather odd\" and an \"angry rant\",<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/iv-drip/melanie-phillips-rather-odd-reaction-to-obamas-win-8297277.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Laura | last=Davis | title=Melanie Phillips' rather odd reaction to Obama's win | date=8 November 2012}}</ref> which \"sparked debate on Twitter\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/11/08/melanie-phillips-barack-obama-blog_n_2091738.html|title=Melanie Phillips Claims Barack Obama's Reelection Brings World War Three 'A Lot Closer'|date=8 November 2012|publisher=The Huffington Post UK}}</ref>\n\nPhillips wrote in defence of president-elect [[Donald Trump]] on 14 November 2016: \"Believing the smears they have created, the Trumpophobes then smear the public for voting for the man they have thus smeared. This, of course, is precisely why millions voted against the liberal establishment and for Trump, as well as for [[Brexit]], in the first place\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/comment/trumps-opponents-are-the-bigots-and-racists-8zsrsp52r|title=Trump's opponents are the bigots and racists|work=The Times|date=14 November 2016|accessdate=14 November 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nA year later she criticised Trump for retweeting videos from [[Britain First]]'s leader [[Jayda Fransen]], calling them \"beyond stupid, reckless and reprehensible.\" She added that \"Trump has given an enormous boost to a group that should be treated as totally beyond the pale. Although campaigning against Islamic extremism, intolerance and religious fascism is not just acceptable but necessary, some groups which do so are totally unacceptable because they themselves promote extremism, intolerance or fascism. Britain First is squarely in that category.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Friedland |first1=Elliot |title=Trump Retweets Posts by Group That Wants to Ban Islam |url=https://clarionproject.org/trump-retweets-britain-first/ |accessdate=16 March 2019 |work=Clarion Project |date=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Climate change====\nPhillips opposes the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]: She has argued that \"there is no evidence for [[global warming]]... the seas are not rising any more than is in any way out of the ordinary, the ice is not decreasing, it is increasing, the [[polar bears]] are increasing in number, and the temperature is going down, not up\".<ref>Melanie Phillips, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yLtmrjh8IBo&t=1m52s \"BBC Question Time, November 2013\"] YouTube, retrieved 24 May 2018</ref> She believes that \"The warming that was observed between 1978\u20131998 has stopped and global temperatures have plateaued.\"<ref>Melanie Phillips [https://www.melaniephillips.com/blow-science-sovereignty-sanity/ \"A Blow for Science, Sovereignty and Sanity\" Published 2 June 2017, Retrieved 24 May 2018]</ref> She has further argued that \"[[Man-made global warming]] theory has been propped up by studies that many scientists have dismissed as methodologically flawed, ideologically bent or even fraudulent.\"<ref name=\"science-dark-ages\">Melanie Phillips [https://www.thegwpf.com/melanie-phillips-science-is-turning-back-to-the-dark-ages/ \"Science is Turning Back to the Dark Ages\"] The Global Warming Policy Forum, retrieved 22 May 2018</ref> She has written that \"The claim that [[CO2 emissions|{{co2}} emissions]] are acidifying the oceans is a favourite of climate-change alarmists\"<ref name=\"science-dark-ages\" /> and that \"claims that [[coral reefs]] are doomed by [[ocean acidification]] are overplayed\".<ref name=\"science-dark-ages\" />\n\nPhillips' published views on these topics have been challenged by scientists and academics, including [[John Krebs, Baron Krebs|John Krebs]] and [[Nicholas Stern, Baron Stern of Brentford|Nicholas Stern]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Carrington |first=Damian |date=21 April 2016 |title=Times's climate change coverage 'distorted' and 'poor quality' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/apr/21/timess-climate-change-coverage-distorted-and-poor-quality |work=The Guardian |location=UK |access-date=25 May 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Phillips |first=Sara |date=21 April 2016 |title=Leading scientists urge UK newspaper The Times to improve 'sub-standard' climate reporting |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-21/leading-scientists-urge-the-times-to-improve-climate-coverage/7345480 |work=ABC News |location=Australia |access-date=25 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Domestic issues===\n====Irish independence====\nPhillips expressed opposition to [[Irish republicanism|Irish independence]], declaring on 7 March 2017 in her column in ''The Times'', that the \"most troublesome bits\" of the UK are \"showing signs of disuniting\". For her, Scottish nationalism and Irish republicanism are cultural phenomena rooted in romanticism and myth\", while Englishness \"came to stand proxy for all the communities of the British Isles\". In particular, she wrote \"Ireland itself has a tenuous claim to nationhood\" because the [[Irish Free State]] was only established in 1922. She denounced \"attempts at secession by tribes\" in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/45e390b0-02b4-11e7-976a-0b4b9a1a67a3|title=Britain is the authentic nation in this battle|work=The Times|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=7 March 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref> ''[[The Irish Times]]'' said that the piece had met with objections from both unionists and republicans. The Irish ambassador to the United States, [[Daniel Mulhall]], said on [[Twitter]] that the country's sovereignty is \"based on strong sense of identity, distinctive culture & shared values and interests\" and rejected her claim.<ref>{{cite news|last=D'Arcy|first=Ciar\u00e1n|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/furious-response-to-column-saying-ireland-has-tenuous-claim-to-nationhood-1.3001173|title=Furious response to column saying Ireland has 'tenuous claim to nationhood'|work=The Irish Times|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is ambivalent about the [[Northern Ireland peace process]], stating that, on the one hand, it has strengthened the [[United Kingdom|Union with Great Britain]] and saved lives, but that, on the other hand, it has rewarded [[terrorism]], \"undermined the [[rule of law]]\", and exchanged bombs for \"[[paramilitary]], [[mafia]]-style control of some areas of [[Northern Ireland]]\".<ref>[http://www.melaniephillips.com/the-faustian-pact-of-the-northern-ireland-peace-process \"The Faustian pact of the Northern Ireland Peace Process\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426214843/http://www.melaniephillips.com/the-faustian-pact-of-the-northern-ireland-peace-process |date=26 April 2014 }}. Melanie Phillips. 23 June 2004. Retrieved 26 April 2014.</ref> In June 2014, in the context of Britain's first entirely secret trial for centuries,<ref>{{Cite news |last = Jones |first = Owen |authorlink = Owen Jones (writer) |date = 5 June 2014 |title = Britain's first secret trial: this way lies trouble |url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jun/05/britain-first-secret-trial-rights |work = [[theguardian.com]] |accessdate = 9 June 2014 }}</ref>  Phillips said that such legal proceedings are justifiable in certain circumstances.<ref>{{Cite news |last = Phillips |first = Melanie |date = 9 June 2014 |title = Sometimes justice has to be done in secret |url = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/columnists/article4112741.ece |newspaper = [[The Times]] |accessdate = 9 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====Party politics====\nShe has argued that the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] lost its way after the retirement of [[Margaret Thatcher]]. She also stated that the [[UK Independence Party]] is prepared to embody \"truly conservative attitudes\" and has attracted a sizeable protest vote, despite its \"unsustainable spending policies\".<ref>[{{cite web|url=http://melaniephillips.com/would-you-buy-a-used-manifesto-promise-from-this-lot|title=Melanie Phillips: Would you buy a used manifesto promise from this lot?]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308030053/http://www.melaniephillips.com/would-you-buy-a-used-manifesto-promise-from-this-lot|archivedate=8 March 2013}}</ref><ref>[{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2287599/I-know-political-common-ground-Dave-The-question-you.html |title=Daily Mail: I know where the political common ground is, Dave. The question is, do you?]|work=Mail Online}}</ref> However, she has also offered tempered praise of [[Tony Blair]]'s attitude to [[Islamic extremism]],<ref>Phillips, Melanie [http://www.familysecuritymatters.org/publications/detail/tony-blair-on-israel-and-islamism-home-truths-and-one-illusion \"Tony Blair on Israel and Islamism: Home Truths and One Illusion\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423192641/http://www.familysecuritymatters.org/publications/detail/tony-blair-on-israel-and-islamism-home-truths-and-one-illusion |date=23 April 2015 }}. ''Family Security Matters''. 12 October 2010. Retrieved 26 April 2014</ref> and she supported his policy of entering the [[Iraq War]].<ref>[http://melaniephillips.com/hysteria-and-irrationality-over-iraq \"Hysteria and irrationality over Iraq\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426202100/http://melaniephillips.com/hysteria-and-irrationality-over-iraq |date=26 April 2014 }}. Melanie Phillips. 24 September 2004. Retrieved 26 April 2014\n.</ref>\n\n====Education====\nIn ''All Must Have Prizes'', published in 1996, Phillips offered a critique of the [[Education in the United Kingdom|British education system]], saying that an egalitarian and non-competitive ethos ([[progressivism]]; [[multicultural education]]) had led to a catastrophic fall in standards. She criticised [[John Dewey]]'s \"disastrous influence\". A subsequent paper said that \"Phillips gets Dewey quite wrong,\" for example in claims that Dewey promoted ahistoric and cultureless education.<ref>Petrovic, J.E. (1998), \"Dewey is a Philistine and other grave misreadings\", ''Oxford Review of Education'' 24 (4), pp. 513\u201320</ref> Phillips criticized one academic paper\u2014on primary-school children's constructions of British identity. Its authors responded with a follow-up study, showing that young adolescents, in common with their counterparts in primary schools, adopt a pluralist viewpoint with virtually no nationalist or racist comments.<ref>Carrington, B., Short, G. (1998), \"Adolescent discourse on national identity\u2014Voices of care and justice?\", ''Educational Studies'' 24 (2), pp. 150\u201352</ref>\n\n====Culture====\nPhillips became a \"scathing critic of modern Britain\" which she regards as \"a debauched and disorderly culture of instant gratification, with disintegrating families, feral children and violence, squalor and vulgarity on the streets\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/jun/16/media.politicsphilosophyandsociety Guardian article]</ref>\n\n====Drugs====\nIn 2008, [[Ruth Runciman]], chair of the UK Drugs Policy Commission, called \"allegations\" Phillips made that the commission was \"intent on bringing about the legalisation of drugs\" \"an absolute travesty and a wilful misrepresentation\".<ref>[https://www.spectator.co.uk/2008/05/uk-drugs-policy-commission-responds-to-melanie-phillips/ \"UK Drugs Policy Commission responds to Melanie Phillips\"], spectator.co.uk. 27 May 2008. Retrieved 16 December 2019.</ref>\n\nPhillips in 2011 said there is no \"war on drugs\" in Britain, rather a \"refusal to enforce the law against drug use in a coherent, consistent, and effective manner\". She sees the result as a lax attitude to drug use that helps perpetuate drug use.<ref name=\"mail\">{{cite web|url=http://melaniephillips.com/drug-legalisation-we-need-it-like-a-hole-in-the-head|title=Drug legalisation? We need it like a hole in the head|author=Melanie Phillips|date=17 November 2011|publisher=melaniephillips.com|accessdate=13 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402140405/http://melaniephillips.com/drug-legalisation-we-need-it-like-a-hole-in-the-head|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> In 2010, she cited the US as an example of strict enforcement, stating \"consumption of cocaine has fallen by 75 per cent in the U.S. over the past 20 years\u2014suggesting that the American 'war on drugs' has been rather successful.\"<ref name=\"dailymail\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/columnists/article-1313508/George-Michael-jailed-pointless-prisons-awash-drugs.html&#93; |title=George Michael being jailed is pointless when our prisons are awash with drugs. |publisher=Daily Mail Online |author= Melanie Phillips|date= 21 September 2010 |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Gay rights====\nShe opposed the introduction of [[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnerships for gay couples in the UK]], and has said that what she calls \"the traditional family [...] has been relentlessly attacked by an alliance of feminists, gay rights activists, divorce lawyers and [[Cultural Marxism|cultural Marxists]] who grasped that this was the surest way to destroy Western society.\"<ref name=\"Melaniephillips.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.melaniephillips.com/a-fatherless-law |title=Melanie Phillips's Articles \" A fatherless law |publisher=Melaniephillips.com |accessdate=28 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609064308/http://www.melaniephillips.com/a-fatherless-law |archivedate=9 June 2011  }}</ref> She has said that giving [[IVF]] fertility treatment to lesbians would \"help destroy our understanding of human identity\", and expressed her opinion that opposition to it represents \"a fightback to save our civilisation\".<ref name=\"Melaniephillips.com\"/> She said the UK government was brainwashing children by including references to gay people in lessons about censuses and population movement.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-1349951/Gayness-mandatory-schools-Gay-victims-prejudice-new-McCarthyites.html \"Yes, gays have often been the victims of prejudice. But they now risk becoming the new McCarthyites\"] By Melanie Phillips, ''Daily Mail'' 24 January 2011]</ref> Philips called it \"an abuse of childhood\", part of a \"ruthless campaign by the gay rights lobby to destroy the very concept of normal sexual behaviour\". She received the 'Bigot of the Year' award from gay equality organisation [[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-20175530 | work=BBC News | title=Storm over Stonewall's Cardinal Keith O'Brien 'bigot' award | date=2 November 2012}}</ref><ref>Hugh Muir, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/oct/30/stonewall-bigot-award-banks-sponsorship \"Stonewall's bigot award prompts banks' threat to withdraw sponsorship\"], ''The Guardian'', 30 October 2012</ref>\n\n====MMR vaccine====\nMelanie Phillips supported [[Andrew Wakefield]], whose [[Lancet MMR autism fraud|fraudulent work]] triggered controversy about the [[MMR vaccine]] and led to his being struck off the medical register. Through numerous articles in the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[The Spectator]]'', Phillips championed Wakefield's claims while casting doubt on their rebuttal by scientists, doctors, and politicians.<ref name=bmj1>{{cite news|author=Helen Bedford & David Elliman|title=MMR: the onslaught continues|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/326/7391/718.1|accessdate=13 November 2013|publisher=BMJ|date=29 March 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Joan|title=The real MMR conspiracy|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/commentators/joan-smith/the-real-mmr-conspiracy-6161828.html|accessdate=13 November 2013|newspaper=The Independent|date=12 September 2004|location=London}}</ref> Her attacks on MMR attracted criticism from scientists and science writers.<ref name=bmj1/><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldacre|first=Ben|title=The MMR sceptic who just doesn't understand science|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/nov/02/health.science|accessdate=13 November 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 November 2005}}</ref><ref name=bmj2>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Michael|title=Why can't the Daily Mail eat humble pie over MMR?|publisher=BMJ, Vol. 331|date=12 November 2005|pmc=1283291}}</ref> Phillips continued to support Wakefield after his research methods and motives began to attract serious scrutiny and criticism: \"While Mr Wakefield is being subjected to a witch-hunt, and while the parents of the affected children are scandalously denied legal aid to pursue the court case which may well have finally brought to light the truth about MMR, those powerful people in the medical establishment are continuing to misrepresent the evidence.\"<ref>[http://www.melaniephillips.com/mmr-the-facade-cracks MMR : the facade cracks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113142000/http://www.melaniephillips.com/mmr-the-facade-cracks |date=13 November 2013 }}, published 7 February 2006, retrieved 13 November 2013.</ref> <ref>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Michael|title=The death agony of the anti-MMR campaign|url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2005/11/11/the-death-agony-of-the-anti-mmr-campaign-2/|accessdate=20 June 2019|newspaper=Spiked|date=11 November 2005}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2010, Andrew Wakefield was struck off the Medical Register for \"serious professional misconduct\", and is currently barred from practising medicine in the UK.<ref name=MeikleBoseley>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2010/may/24/mmr-doctor-andrew-wakefield-struck-off |title=MMR row doctor Andrew Wakefield struck off register |work=The Guardian|date= 24 May 2010|accessdate=24 May 2010 | location=London | last1= Meikle|first1=James|first2=Sarah|last2=Boseley| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527003931/http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2010/may/24/mmr-doctor-andrew-wakefield-struck-off| archivedate= 27 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Phillips's support of Wakefield's \"findings\" and her campaign against the MMR vaccine has been both widely noted,<ref name=falseprophets/><ref name=dean>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UFJSxmvYymEC&pg=PA318&dq=Tammy+Boyce+Health,+Risk+and+News&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kfaDUsblKcKrtAaF3oDYBw&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Melanie%20Phillips&f=false Malcolm Dean. ''Democracy Under Attack: How the Media Distort Policy and Politics''] The Policy Press, 2012: p. 371.</ref> and credited for significantly undermining public trust in vaccines.<ref name=falseprophets>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_epul7PlKccC&pg=PT65&lpg=PT65&dq=Melanie+Phillips+MMR+vaccine&source=bl&ots=0MqKXf5NAF&sig=qI6qOHeCyICxGpnWfrvMmFCOxWQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=APSDUuzXIKWm4AT7q4HoBA&ved=0CFgQ6AEwBjhG#v=onepage&q=Melanie%20Phillips%20MMR%20vaccine&f=false Paul A. Offit. ''Autism's False Prophets: Bad Science, Risky Medicine, and the Search for a Cure''] Columbia University Press, 2013: p.  56.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPhillips is married to [[Joshua Rozenberg]], former legal affairs editor for the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noelgay.com/html/artist_corporate.php?id=200 |title=Joshua Rozenberg |publisher=Noel Gay |accessdate=11 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719184424/http://www.noelgay.com/html/artist_corporate.php?id=200 |archivedate=19 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=NVXK4rGx9IG%2BYowDAXJhXQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=22 June 2017|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> They have two children.<ref name=\"Ashley2006\">{{cite news|last=Ashley|first=Jackie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/jun/16/media.politicsphilosophyandsociety|title=The multicultural menace, anti-semitism and me|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 June 2006|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n* ''The Divided House: Women at Westminster'', Sidgwick and Jackson, 1980, {{ISBN|0-283-98547-X}}.\n* ''Doctors' Dilemmas: Medical Ethics and Contemporary Science'' by Melanie Phillips & John Dawson, Harvester Press, 1985, {{ISBN|0-7108-0983-2}}.\n* ''All Must Have Prizes'', Warner, 1998, {{ISBN|0-7515-2274-0}}.\n* ''The Sex-Change Society: Feminised Britain and the Neutered Male'', Social Market Foundation, 1999, {{ISBN|1-874097-64-X}}.\n* ''America's Social Revolution'', Civitas: Institute for the Study of Civil Society, 2001, {{ISBN|1-903386-15-2}}.\n* ''The Ascent of Woman: A History of the Suffragette Movement and the Ideas Behind it'', Little, Brown, 2003, {{ISBN|0-316-72533-1}}.\n* ''[[Londonistan (book)|Londonistan: How Britain Is Creating a Terror State Within]]'', Gibson Square Books Ltd, 2006, {{ISBN|1-903933-76-5}}.\n* ''The World Turned Upside Down: The Global Battle Over God, Truth and Power'', New York, Encounter Books, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-59403-375-9}}.\n* ''Guardian Angel: My Story, My Britain'', emBooks, 1 edition (1 May 2013), {{ASIN|B00CMA0KP6}}\n* ''The Legacy'' (novel), Bombardier Books, 2018 {{ISBN|978-1-68261-566-9}}\n* ''Guardian Angel: My Journey from Leftism to Sanity,'' Bombardier Books, 2018.<ref name=\"TellerReview\">{{cite news |last1=Teller |first1=Neville |title=A journalist's journey The transformational autobiography of Melanie Phillips (bok review) |url=https://www.jpost.com/Jerusalem-Report/A-journalists-journey-583474 |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher=Jerusalem Report |date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{official website|www.melaniephillips.com|Melanie Phillips}} \u2013 official site\n*{{C-SPAN|Melanie Phillips}}\n**[http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/311970-1 Melanie Phillips] ''[[In Depth]]'' interview on [[C-SPAN]], 5 May 2013\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phillips, Melanie}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Jews]]\n[[Category:British conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:British critics of Islam]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:British radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n[[Category:The Sunday Times people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Putney High School]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:British social commentators]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       = File:Melanie Phillips.jpg\n| caption     = Phillips in 2014\n| name        = Melanie Phillips\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1951|6|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = {{Hlist | Journalist | Author | Publisher }}\n| title       = \n| family      =\n| spouse      = [[Joshua Rozenberg]]\n| children    = \n| relatives   = \n| ethnicity   = \n| religion    = \n| alma_mater  = [[St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| credits     = {{Unbulleted list|item_style=white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.3em; margin-bottom: 0.3em | ''[[The Times]]'' columnist | Former columnist for <br />  ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Spectator]]''<br>and the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' |  | Author of ''[[Londonistan (book)|Londonistan]]'' }}\n| URL         = \n}}\n'''Melanie Phillips''' (born 4 June 1951) is a British journalist, author, and public commentator. She began her career writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''[[New Statesman]]''. During the 1990s, she came to identify with ideas more associated with the right and currently writes for ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', and ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'', covering political and social issues from a [[Social conservatism|social conservative]] perspective. Phillips, quoting [[Irving Kristol]], defines herself as a [[classical liberalism|liberal]] who has \"been mugged by reality\".<ref name=\"Beckett\">Andy Beckett [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/mar/07/dailymail.pressandpublishing/print \"The changing face of Melanie Phillips\"], ''The Guardian'', 7 March 2003.</ref>\n\nPhillips has appeared as a panellist on the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[The Moral Maze]]'' and [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]''. She was awarded the [[Orwell Prize#Journalism category|Orwell Prize for Journalism]] in 1996, while she was writing for ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref name=\"OP profile\">{{cite web | url= http://theorwellprize.co.uk/shortlists/melanie-phillips/| title= Orwell Prize Melanie Phillips \u2013 Columnist, Daily Mail|date=|accessdate=25 November 2011| work=The Orwell Prize}}</ref> Her books include the memoir ''Guardian Angel: My Story, My Britain''.<ref>{{cite news| first=Gaby | last=Hinsliff | url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/17/guardian-angel-melanie-phillips-review#start-of-comments | title=Guardian Angel: My Story, My Britain by Melanie Phillips \u2013 review | work=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 May 2013|accessdate=25 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMelanie Phillips was born in [[Hammersmith]], the daughter of Mabel (n\u00e9e Cohen) and Alfred Phillips.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=aZJuIULum%2Fwl2BcBJsB4SA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=22 June 2017|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> Her family is Jewish and emigrated to Britain from Poland and Russia.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2319192/Why-Left-hates-families-MELANIE-PHIILLIPS-reveals-selfish-sneers-Guardianistas-Left-actively-fosters--revels--family-breakdown-.html Why the Left hates families: Melanie Phillips reveals how the selfish sneers of Guardianistas made her see how the Left actively fosters \u2013 and revels in \u2013 family breakdown...], ''[[Daily Mail]]'', 3 May 2013</ref> According to her account, the name \"Phillips\" was imposed by British officials who were unable to pronounce her family's Polish name. She describes her family as \"poor\" people living as outsiders in an impoverished area of London, who \"kept their heads down and tried to assimilate\".<ref name=\"auto1\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2320940/MELANIE-PHILLIPS-Too-immigrants-today-expect-Britain-adopt-THEIR-culture.html Daily Mail article]</ref> Her father, Alfred, was a dress salesman, while her mother, Mabel, ran a children's clothes shop and both were committed [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] voters.<ref name=\"Beckett\"/>  She has stated that her father was \"gentle, kind and innocent\", an \"overgrown child\", and that \"as my other parent he just wasn\u2019t there\", which taught her \"how the absence of proper fathering could screw up a child for life\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> She was educated at [[Putney High School]], a girls' fee-paying [[independent school]] in [[Putney]], London. Later she read English at [[St Anne's College, Oxford]].<ref>The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History, ed. William D. Rubinstein, et. al., Palgrave Macmillan, 2011, p. 753</ref>\n\n==Journalism career==\nPhillips trained as a journalist on the ''Evening Echo'', a local newspaper in [[Hemel Hempstead]],<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> as her probationary period in the provinces, then compulsory for the profession. After winning the Young Journalist of the Year award in 1976,<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> she spent a short period at the ''[[New Society (magazine)|New Society]]'' magazine.\n\nShe joined ''The Guardian'' newspaper in 1977, becoming its social services correspondent and social policy leader writer. In 1984, she became the paper's news editor,<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> and was reported to have fainted on her first day.<ref name=\"Hillmore\">Peter Hillmore [http://www.newstatesman.com/200303100018 \"NS Profile - Melanie Phillips\"], ''New Statesman'', 10 March 2003</ref> In 1982, she defended the Labour Party at the time of the split with the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]]. Her opinion column began in 1987. While working for ''The Guardian'', Phillips was persuaded to write a play called ''Traitors'' by [[Julia Pascal]], who directed it.<ref name=\"Phillips2017\">{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/words-i-thought-id-never-write-im-a-novelist-kdnjlvqc0|title=Words I thought I'd never write: I'm a novelist|work=The Times|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref> It was performed at [[the Drill Hall]] from January 1986. The play was set at the time of the [[1982 Lebanon War]] and centred around the moral dilemmas of a Jewish journalist who as political editor of a liberal magazine has to decide whether to veto an article written in anti-semitic tones, and also whether she is right to publish a leaked document about the [[Falklands War]]. The play was reviewed by [[John Peter (critic)|John Peter]] in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' as \"a play of blistering intelligence and fearless moral questioning\", although he considered it bordering on implausible.<ref>[[John Peter (critic)|John Peter]]. \"Amoral acquiescence\". ''The Sunday Times''. 26 January 1986.</ref> According to Phillips, writing in December 2017, it was the only positive review the play received.<ref name=\"Phillips2017\"/> Phillips left ''The Guardian'' in 1993, saying that her relationship with the paper and its readers had become \"like a really horrific family argument\",<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> and that she had seen the \"reality\" that \"the west ha[d] lost its moral compass\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She took her opinion column to ''The Guardian''{{'s}} sister-paper ''[[The Observer]]'', then to ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' in 1998,<ref name=\"Hillmore\"/> before beginning her association with the tabloid ''[[Daily Mail]]'' in 2001. She also writes for ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'', ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' and other periodicals. \n\nIn November 2010, ''The Spectator'' and Phillips apologised and agreed to pay substantial compensation and legal costs to a prominent British Muslim they falsely accused of antisemitism.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/25/spectator-apology-muslim-antisemitism|title=The Spectator apologises for falsely accusing Muslim of antisemitism|last=Halliday|first=Josh|date=25 November 2010|accessdate=27 September 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The following year, she resigned from the magazine after it apologised and paid compensation for another of her pieces which, it said, contained an allegation that was \"completely false\".<ref name=guardian1>{{cite news | url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2011/jun/28/the-spectator-blogging | title=Why Melanie Phillips quit The Spectator|date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=4 May 2013| work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Roy | last=Greenslade}}</ref>\n\nSince 2003, she has written a blog, once hosted by ''[[The Spectator]]'', but following her resignation from the magazine in June 2011,<ref name=guardian1 /><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2011/06/melanie-phillips-spectator | title=Goodbye, Melanie!|date=24 June 2011 |accessdate=4 May 2013| work=News Statesman (blog)}}</ref> it is hosted on her website.<ref>{{cite web|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|title=My blog's new home|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/melaniephillips/7029239/my-blogs-new-home.thtml|publisher=The Spectator|accessdate=17 December 2011|date=16 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507210447/http://www.spectator.co.uk/melaniephillips/7029239/my-blogs-new-home.thtml|archivedate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In September 2013, it emerged that her ''Mail'' column was to end, although according to Phillips, the newspaper wanted her to continue to write features and other articles for it.<ref>William Turvill [http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/melanie-phillips-bows-out-after-12-years-mail-columnist-dominic-lawson-tipped-replace-her \"Melanie Phillips bows out after 12 years as Mail columnist, Dominic Lawson tipped to replace her\"], ''Press Gazette'', 12 September 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2013, she launched an [[e-book]] publishing company called emBooks, to promote her book, together with several others, and self-promotional merchandise to the US market.<ref name=\"embooks\">{{cite news| first=Charlie | last=Cooper | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/online/phillips-launches-brand-melanie-as-she-tries-to-become-the-darling-of-the-american-right-8604621.html | title=Phillips launches 'Brand Melanie' as she tries to become the darling of the American right | work=[[The Independent]] | date=5 May 2013 | accessdate=25 August 2013 | location=London}}</ref> She currently writes for ''[[The Times]]''.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/profile/melanie-phillips</ref>\n\nShe has a weekly radio show on [[Voice of Israel]], is a regular panellist on BBC Radio's ''[[The Moral Maze]]'' and appears frequently on BBC TV's signature political shows ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' and ''[[The Daily Politics]]''.\n\n==Views and opinions==\nThe BBC has said that Phillips \"is regarded as one of the [British] media's leading right-wing voices\" and a \"controversial\" columnist.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/programmes/question_time/6727447.stm List of Panelists] for [[Question Time (TV series)|''Question Time'']], BBC website, 6 June 2007.</ref> [[Nick Cohen]] wrote in 2011 that she has become [[Defamation|vilified]] by ''The Guardian''.<ref name=\"Cohen2011\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Nick|authorlink=Nick Cohen|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/nickcohen/7457633/a-regiment-of-women-monsterers.thtml|title=A regiment of women monsterers|work=[[The Spectator]]|date=6 December 2011|access-date=17 December 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111208022649/http://www.spectator.co.uk/nickcohen/7457633/a-regiment-of-women-monsterers.thtml|archive-date=8 December 2011}}</ref> Phillips herself stated in 2006, during an interview with [[Jackie Ashley]] for the newspaper, that it often misrepresents her opinions.<ref name=\"Ashley2006\"/>\n\n===International issues===\n\n====Islamophobia====\nPhillips was heavily criticised for an article she wrote in the Jewish Chronicle which suggested that \u201cthe taunt of Islamophobia is used to silence any criticism of the Islamic world, including Islamic extremism\u201d and \u201cfacilitates\u201d antisemitism. The editor of the Jewish Chronicle, while not offering regret for publishing the article, did acknowledge that the article had been divisive and apologised to readers who had been angered or upset by the piece. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/news/2019/dec/17/islamophobia-a-bogus-label-jewish-chronicle-under-fire-over-story</ref>\n\n====Iran====\nShe is a staunch critic of [[Iran]] and has written and spoken frequently about the threat she perceives it to be, particularly if it were to obtain nuclear weapons.<ref>{{cite news|first=Melanie | last=Phillips | url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/features/24356/hezbollah-cells-await-irans-orders/ | title=Hezbollah cells await Iran's orders | work=[[The Spectator]] | date=2 August 2006 | accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MPdailymail\">{{cite news|first=Melanie | last=Phillips | url=http://phillipsblog.dailymail.co.uk/2012/01/why-iran-will-not-come-to-its-senses.html | title=Why Iran will not 'come to its senses' | work=[[Mail Online]] | date=25 January 2012 | accessdate=21 June 2013 | location=London}}</ref> The Iranian regime, she writes, \"has seen itself at war with the west ever since it [[Iranian Revolution|came to power]] in 1979, and which has been involved in arguably every major terrorist atrocity against it\". In her view, Iran's leaders are \"religious fanatics\" who are \"impervious to reason\" and who \"would be happy\" to bring about an [[Islamic eschatology|apocalyptic]] [[End time|end of days]]. Thus, \"there is no alternative to force if it is to be stopped.\"<ref name=\"MPdailymail\" /> She has drawn criticism for her hard-line approach from various commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/oct/31/melanie-phillips-islamism-spectator|title=The personal jihad of Melanie Phillips|date=31 October 2009|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jun/18/melanie-phillips-rightwing|title=What drove Melanie Phillips to the right?|date=18 June 2010|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nShe has said that she supports a [[two-state solution]] in theory but that it cannot work in practice, commenting: \"I would have no problem with a Palestine that would live in peace alongside Israel ... I respond to the evidence of what is actually happening. Israel is being demonised ... If Israel were to leave the West Bank, it would turn Islamist overnight and become an Iranian proxy on Israel's doorstep. That is why I cannot support a state of Palestine.\"<ref name=fpm>{{cite news |url=http://www.frontpagemag.com/readArticle.aspx?ARTID=35689 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20170524222747/http://archive.frontpagemag.com/readArticle.aspx?ARTID=35689 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 May 2017 |publisher=[[FrontPage Magazine]] |date=24 July 2009 |title=Alan Dershowitz vs. Melanie Phillips |first=Jamie |last=Glazov |accessdate=2 August 2009  }}</ref>\n\nPhillips's criticisms of liberal Jews who disagree with her positions on Israel have been mocked or condemned by writers such as [[Alan Dershowitz]],<ref name=\"The Spectator 9 July 2009\">{{cite news |url= http://www.spectator.co.uk/2009/07/a-reply-to-melanie-phillips/|title= A reply to Melanie Phillips |last= Dershowitz | first = Alan|date= 9 July 2009|work= [[The Spectator]] |publisher= [[Press Holdings]]| accessdate= 10 May 2016 }}</ref> Rabbi David Goldberg,<ref>\"... it would have to be someone particularly dim who begins a conversation with me at one of those north London dinner parties where writers such as... Melanie Phillips... claim to have been shocked by the anti-semitic hostility of the chattering classes...\" in \"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/jan/26/religion.uk1 Let's have a sense of proportion]\" by Rabbi David Goldberg, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 January 2002</ref> and [[Jonathan Freedland]] who criticised Phillips's labelling of [[Independent Jewish Voices]], a group of liberal Jews, as \"Jews For Genocide\". Freedland wrote in ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'': \"Now, as it happens, I have multiple criticisms of IJV ... but even their most trenchant opponents must surely blanch at the notion that these critics of Israel and of Anglo-Jewish officialdom are somehow in favour of genocide\u2014literally, eager to see the murder and eradication of the Jewish people ... it is an absurdity, one that drains the word 'genocide' of any meaning\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Freedland, Jonathan|url=http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=51460&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchstr=eager%20to%20see%20the%20murder%20and%20eradication%20of%20the%20Jewish%20people&srchtxt=0&srchhead=1&srchauthor=0&srchsandp=0&scsrch=0|title=The danger of Melanie Phillips|newspaper=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=30 March 2007|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005065425/http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=51460&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchstr=eager%20to%20see%20the%20murder%20and%20eradication%20of%20the%20Jewish%20people&srchtxt=0&srchhead=1&srchauthor=0&srchsandp=0&scsrch=0|archivedate=5 October 2011|author-link = Jonathan Freedland}}</ref>\n\n====United States====\nEarly in the presidency of [[Barack Obama]], Phillips accused him of \"adopting the agenda of the Islamist\" and of being \"firmly in the Islamists' camp\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/oct/31/melanie-phillips-islamism-spectator | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Ed | last=Husain | title=The personal jihad of Melanie Phillips | date=31 October 2009}}</ref> Shortly after Obama's re-election for a second term, Phillips said that \"Four years ago, America put into the White House a sulky narcissist with an unbroken history of involvement in thuggish, corrupt, far-left, black power, Jew-bashing, west-hating politics\". She warned that Obama would lead America into a \"terrifying darkness\". ''[[The Independent]]'' termed it \"rather odd\" and an \"angry rant\",<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/iv-drip/melanie-phillips-rather-odd-reaction-to-obamas-win-8297277.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Laura | last=Davis | title=Melanie Phillips' rather odd reaction to Obama's win | date=8 November 2012}}</ref> which \"sparked debate on Twitter\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/11/08/melanie-phillips-barack-obama-blog_n_2091738.html|title=Melanie Phillips Claims Barack Obama's Reelection Brings World War Three 'A Lot Closer'|date=8 November 2012|publisher=The Huffington Post UK}}</ref>\n\nPhillips wrote in defence of president-elect [[Donald Trump]] on 14 November 2016: \"Believing the smears they have created, the Trumpophobes then smear the public for voting for the man they have thus smeared. This, of course, is precisely why millions voted against the liberal establishment and for Trump, as well as for [[Brexit]], in the first place\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/comment/trumps-opponents-are-the-bigots-and-racists-8zsrsp52r|title=Trump's opponents are the bigots and racists|work=The Times|date=14 November 2016|accessdate=14 November 2016}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nA year later she criticised Trump for retweeting videos from [[Britain First]]'s leader [[Jayda Fransen]], calling them \"beyond stupid, reckless and reprehensible.\" She added that \"Trump has given an enormous boost to a group that should be treated as totally beyond the pale. Although campaigning against Islamic extremism, intolerance and religious fascism is not just acceptable but necessary, some groups which do so are totally unacceptable because they themselves promote extremism, intolerance or fascism. Britain First is squarely in that category.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Friedland |first1=Elliot |title=Trump Retweets Posts by Group That Wants to Ban Islam |url=https://clarionproject.org/trump-retweets-britain-first/ |accessdate=16 March 2019 |work=Clarion Project |date=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Climate change====\nPhillips opposes the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]: She has argued that \"there is no evidence for [[global warming]]... the seas are not rising any more than is in any way out of the ordinary, the ice is not decreasing, it is increasing, the [[polar bears]] are increasing in number, and the temperature is going down, not up\".<ref>Melanie Phillips, [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yLtmrjh8IBo&t=1m52s \"BBC Question Time, November 2013\"] YouTube, retrieved 24 May 2018</ref> She believes that \"The warming that was observed between 1978\u20131998 has stopped and global temperatures have plateaued.\"<ref>Melanie Phillips [https://www.melaniephillips.com/blow-science-sovereignty-sanity/ \"A Blow for Science, Sovereignty and Sanity\" Published 2 June 2017, Retrieved 24 May 2018]</ref> She has further argued that \"[[Man-made global warming]] theory has been propped up by studies that many scientists have dismissed as methodologically flawed, ideologically bent or even fraudulent.\"<ref name=\"science-dark-ages\">Melanie Phillips [https://www.thegwpf.com/melanie-phillips-science-is-turning-back-to-the-dark-ages/ \"Science is Turning Back to the Dark Ages\"] The Global Warming Policy Forum, retrieved 22 May 2018</ref> She has written that \"The claim that [[CO2 emissions|{{co2}} emissions]] are acidifying the oceans is a favourite of climate-change alarmists\"<ref name=\"science-dark-ages\" /> and that \"claims that [[coral reefs]] are doomed by [[ocean acidification]] are overplayed\".<ref name=\"science-dark-ages\" />\n\nIn contrast, the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) assesses that it is \"extremely likely\"<ref>The IPCC defines \"extremely likely\" as indicating a probability of 95 to 100%, based on an expert assessment of all the available evidence. {{harvnb|IPCC AR5 WG1|2013}}, Section: [http://www.climatechange2013.org/images/report/WG1AR5_SPM_FINAL.pdf Summary for Policymakers (finalized version)], page 4, footnote 2.</ref> that human influence was the dominant cause of global warming between 1951 and 2010,<ref>{{harvnb|IPCC AR5 WG1|2013}}, Section: [http://www.climatechange2013.org/images/report/WG1AR5_SPM_FINAL.pdf Summary for Policymakers (finalized version)], Chapter: D.3 Detection and Attribution of Climate Change, page 17.  </ref> with the best estimate being that the observed warming since 1951 has been entirely human caused.<ref>\"The likely range of the human contribution to the global mean temperature increase over the period 1951\u20132010 is 1.1\u00b0 to 1.4\u00b0F (0.6\u00b0 to 0.8\u00b0C), and the central estimate of the observed warming of 1.2\u00b0F (0.65\u00b0C) lies within this range (high confidence). This translates to a likely human contribution of 93%\u2013123% of the observed 1951\u20132010 change.\" [https://science2017.globalchange.gov/chapter/3/ Chapter 3: Detection and Attribution of Climate Change], ''Climate Science Special Report '', U.S. Global Change Research Program.</ref> \nSimilarly, between 1751 and 1996, globally averaged surface ocean [[pH]] is estimated to have decreased from approximately 8.25 to 8.14 in response to the dissolution of anthropogenic {{co2}},<ref name=jacob05>{{cite journal | last=Jacobson | first=M. Z. | year=2005 | title=Studying ocean acidification with conservative, stable numerical schemes for nonequilibrium air-ocean exchange and ocean equilibrium chemistry | journal=[[Journal of Geophysical Research: Atmospheres]] | volume=110 | issue=D7 | doi=10.1029/2004JD005220 | pages=D07302 | bibcode=2005JGRD..110.7302J | ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"scor-int\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scor-int.org/OBO2009/A&O_Report.pdf|title=Report of the Ocean Acidification and Oxygen Working Group, International Council for Science's Scientific Committee on Ocean Research (SCOR) Biological Observatories Workshop}}</ref> and numerous field experiments have found this deleterious to coral reefs.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mollica|first1=Nathaniel R.|last2=Guo|first2=Weifu|last3=Cohen|first3=Anne L.|last4=Huang|first4=Kuo-Fang|last5=Foster|first5=Gavin L.|last6=Donald|first6=Hannah K.|last7=Solow|first7=Andrew R.|title=Ocean acidification affects coral growth by reducing skeletal density|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|date=20 February 2018|volume=115|issue=8|pages=1754\u20131759|doi=10.1073/pnas.1712806115|pmid=29378969|bibcode=2018PNAS..115.1754M|pmc=5828584}}</ref><ref name=\"Albright2018\">{{cite journal|last1= Albright|first1= R.|last2= Takeshita|first2= T.|last3= Koweek|first3=D. A.|last4= Ninokawa|first4= A.|last5= Wolfe|first5= K.|last6= Rivlin|first6= T.|last7= Nebuchina|first7= Y.|last8= Young|first8= J.|last9= Caldeira|first9= K.|title= Carbon dioxide addition to coral reef waters suppresses net community calcification |journal= Nature|date= 14 March 2018|volume= 555|issue= 7697|pages= 516\u2013519|doi= 10.1038/nature25968|pmid= 29539634|bibcode= 2018Natur.555..516A}}</ref>\nPhillips' published views on these topics have been challenged by leading scientists and academics, including [[John Krebs, Baron Krebs|John Krebs]] and [[Nicholas Stern, Baron Stern of Brentford|Nicholas Stern]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Carrington |first=Damian |date=21 April 2016 |title=Times's climate change coverage 'distorted' and 'poor quality' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/apr/21/timess-climate-change-coverage-distorted-and-poor-quality |work=The Guardian |location=UK |access-date=25 May 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Phillips |first=Sara |date=21 April 2016 |title=Leading scientists urge UK newspaper The Times to improve 'sub-standard' climate reporting |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-21/leading-scientists-urge-the-times-to-improve-climate-coverage/7345480 |work=ABC News |location=Australia |access-date=25 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Domestic issues===\n====Irish independence====\nPhillips expressed opposition to [[Irish republicanism|Irish independence]], declaring on 7 March 2017 in her column in ''The Times'', that the \"most troublesome bits\" of the UK are \"showing signs of disuniting\". For her, Scottish nationalism and Irish republicanism are cultural phenomena rooted in romanticism and myth\", while Englishness \"came to stand proxy for all the communities of the British Isles\". In particular, she wrote \"Ireland itself has a tenuous claim to nationhood\" because the [[Irish Free State]] was only established in 1922. She denounced \"attempts at secession by tribes\" in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips|first=Melanie|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/45e390b0-02b4-11e7-976a-0b4b9a1a67a3|title=Britain is the authentic nation in this battle|work=The Times|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=7 March 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref> ''[[The Irish Times]]'' said that the piece had met with objections from both unionists and republicans. The Irish ambassador to the United States, [[Daniel Mulhall]], said on [[Twitter]] that the country's sovereignty is \"based on strong sense of identity, distinctive culture & shared values and interests\" and rejected her claim.<ref>{{cite news|last=D'Arcy|first=Ciar\u00e1n|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/furious-response-to-column-saying-ireland-has-tenuous-claim-to-nationhood-1.3001173|title=Furious response to column saying Ireland has 'tenuous claim to nationhood'|work=The Irish Times|date=7 March 2017|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is ambivalent about the [[Northern Ireland peace process]], stating that, on the one hand, it has strengthened the [[United Kingdom|Union with Great Britain]] and saved lives, but that, on the other hand, it has rewarded [[terrorism]], \"undermined the [[rule of law]]\", and exchanged bombs for \"[[paramilitary]], [[mafia]]-style control of some areas of [[Northern Ireland]]\".<ref>[http://www.melaniephillips.com/the-faustian-pact-of-the-northern-ireland-peace-process \"The Faustian pact of the Northern Ireland Peace Process\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426214843/http://www.melaniephillips.com/the-faustian-pact-of-the-northern-ireland-peace-process |date=26 April 2014 }}. Melanie Phillips. 23 June 2004. Retrieved 26 April 2014.</ref> In June 2014, in the context of Britain's first entirely secret trial for centuries,<ref>{{Cite news |last = Jones |first = Owen |authorlink = Owen Jones (writer) |date = 5 June 2014 |title = Britain's first secret trial: this way lies trouble |url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jun/05/britain-first-secret-trial-rights |work = [[theguardian.com]] |accessdate = 9 June 2014 }}</ref>  Phillips said that such legal proceedings are justifiable in certain circumstances.<ref>{{Cite news |last = Phillips |first = Melanie |date = 9 June 2014 |title = Sometimes justice has to be done in secret |url = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/columnists/article4112741.ece |newspaper = [[The Times]] |accessdate = 9 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====Party politics====\nShe has argued that the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] lost its way after the retirement of [[Margaret Thatcher]]. She also stated that the [[UK Independence Party]] is prepared to embody \"truly conservative attitudes\" and has attracted a sizeable protest vote, despite its \"unsustainable spending policies\".<ref>[{{cite web|url=http://melaniephillips.com/would-you-buy-a-used-manifesto-promise-from-this-lot|title=Melanie Phillips: Would you buy a used manifesto promise from this lot?]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308030053/http://www.melaniephillips.com/would-you-buy-a-used-manifesto-promise-from-this-lot|archivedate=8 March 2013}}</ref><ref>[{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2287599/I-know-political-common-ground-Dave-The-question-you.html |title=Daily Mail: I know where the political common ground is, Dave. The question is, do you?]|work=Mail Online}}</ref> However, she has also offered tempered praise of [[Tony Blair]]'s attitude to [[Islamic extremism]],<ref>Phillips, Melanie [http://www.familysecuritymatters.org/publications/detail/tony-blair-on-israel-and-islamism-home-truths-and-one-illusion \"Tony Blair on Israel and Islamism: Home Truths and One Illusion\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423192641/http://www.familysecuritymatters.org/publications/detail/tony-blair-on-israel-and-islamism-home-truths-and-one-illusion |date=23 April 2015 }}. ''Family Security Matters''. 12 October 2010. Retrieved 26 April 2014</ref> and she supported his policy of entering the [[Iraq War]].<ref>[http://melaniephillips.com/hysteria-and-irrationality-over-iraq \"Hysteria and irrationality over Iraq\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426202100/http://melaniephillips.com/hysteria-and-irrationality-over-iraq |date=26 April 2014 }}. Melanie Phillips. 24 September 2004. Retrieved 26 April 2014\n.</ref>\n\n====Education====\nIn ''All Must Have Prizes'', published in 1996, Phillips offered a critique of the [[Education in the United Kingdom|British education system]], saying that an egalitarian and non-competitive ethos ([[progressivism]]; [[multicultural education]]) had led to a catastrophic fall in standards. She criticised [[John Dewey]]'s \"disastrous influence\". A subsequent paper said that \"Phillips gets Dewey quite wrong,\" for example in claims that Dewey promoted ahistoric and cultureless education.<ref>Petrovic, J.E. (1998), \"Dewey is a Philistine and other grave misreadings\", ''Oxford Review of Education'' 24 (4), pp. 513\u201320</ref> Phillips criticized one academic paper\u2014on primary-school children's constructions of British identity. Its authors responded with a follow-up study, showing that young adolescents, in common with their counterparts in primary schools, adopt a pluralist viewpoint with virtually no nationalist or racist comments.<ref>Carrington, B., Short, G. (1998), \"Adolescent discourse on national identity\u2014Voices of care and justice?\", ''Educational Studies'' 24 (2), pp. 150\u201352</ref>\n\n====Culture====\nPhillips became a \"scathing critic of modern Britain\" which she regards as \"a debauched and disorderly culture of instant gratification, with disintegrating families, feral children and violence, squalor and vulgarity on the streets\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/jun/16/media.politicsphilosophyandsociety Guardian article]</ref>\n\n====Drugs====\nIn 2008, [[Ruth Runciman]], chair of the UK Drugs Policy Commission, called \"allegations\" Phillips made that the commission was \"intent on bringing about the legalisation of drugs\" \"an absolute travesty and a wilful misrepresentation\".<ref>[https://www.spectator.co.uk/2008/05/uk-drugs-policy-commission-responds-to-melanie-phillips/ \"UK Drugs Policy Commission responds to Melanie Phillips\"], spectator.co.uk. 27 May 2008. Retrieved 16 December 2019.</ref>\n\nPhillips in 2011 said there is no \"war on drugs\" in Britain, rather a \"refusal to enforce the law against drug use in a coherent, consistent, and effective manner\". She sees the result as a lax attitude to drug use that helps perpetuate drug use.<ref name=\"mail\">{{cite web|url=http://melaniephillips.com/drug-legalisation-we-need-it-like-a-hole-in-the-head|title=Drug legalisation? We need it like a hole in the head|author=Melanie Phillips|date=17 November 2011|publisher=melaniephillips.com|accessdate=13 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402140405/http://melaniephillips.com/drug-legalisation-we-need-it-like-a-hole-in-the-head|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> In 2010, she cited the US as an example of strict enforcement, stating \"consumption of cocaine has fallen by 75 per cent in the U.S. over the past 20 years\u2014suggesting that the American 'war on drugs' has been rather successful.\"<ref name=\"dailymail\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/columnists/article-1313508/George-Michael-jailed-pointless-prisons-awash-drugs.html&#93; |title=George Michael being jailed is pointless when our prisons are awash with drugs. |publisher=Daily Mail Online |author= Melanie Phillips|date= 21 September 2010 |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Gay rights====\nShe opposed the introduction of [[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnerships for gay couples in the UK]], and has said that what she calls \"the traditional family [...] has been relentlessly attacked by an alliance of feminists, gay rights activists, divorce lawyers and [[Cultural Marxism|cultural Marxists]] who grasped that this was the surest way to destroy Western society.\"<ref name=\"Melaniephillips.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.melaniephillips.com/a-fatherless-law |title=Melanie Phillips's Articles \" A fatherless law |publisher=Melaniephillips.com |accessdate=28 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609064308/http://www.melaniephillips.com/a-fatherless-law |archivedate=9 June 2011  }}</ref> She has said that giving [[IVF]] fertility treatment to lesbians would \"help destroy our understanding of human identity\", and expressed her opinion that opposition to it represents \"a fightback to save our civilisation\".<ref name=\"Melaniephillips.com\"/> She said the UK government was brainwashing children by including references to gay people in lessons about censuses and population movement.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-1349951/Gayness-mandatory-schools-Gay-victims-prejudice-new-McCarthyites.html \"Yes, gays have often been the victims of prejudice. But they now risk becoming the new McCarthyites\"] By Melanie Phillips, ''Daily Mail'' 24 January 2011]</ref> Philips called it \"an abuse of childhood\", part of a \"ruthless campaign by the gay rights lobby to destroy the very concept of normal sexual behaviour\". She received the 'Bigot of the Year' award from gay equality organisation [[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-20175530 | work=BBC News | title=Storm over Stonewall's Cardinal Keith O'Brien 'bigot' award | date=2 November 2012}}</ref><ref>Hugh Muir, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/oct/30/stonewall-bigot-award-banks-sponsorship \"Stonewall's bigot award prompts banks' threat to withdraw sponsorship\"], ''The Guardian'', 30 October 2012</ref>\n\n====MMR vaccine====\nMelanie Phillips supported [[Andrew Wakefield]], whose [[Lancet MMR autism fraud|fraudulent work]] triggered controversy about the [[MMR vaccine]] and led to his being struck off the medical register. Through numerous articles in the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[The Spectator]]'', Phillips championed Wakefield's claims while casting doubt on their rebuttal by scientists, doctors, and politicians.<ref name=bmj1>{{cite news|author=Helen Bedford & David Elliman|title=MMR: the onslaught continues|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/326/7391/718.1|accessdate=13 November 2013|publisher=BMJ|date=29 March 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Joan|title=The real MMR conspiracy|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/commentators/joan-smith/the-real-mmr-conspiracy-6161828.html|accessdate=13 November 2013|newspaper=The Independent|date=12 September 2004|location=London}}</ref> Her attacks on MMR attracted criticism from scientists and science writers.<ref name=bmj1/><ref>{{cite news|last=Goldacre|first=Ben|title=The MMR sceptic who just doesn't understand science|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/nov/02/health.science|accessdate=13 November 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 November 2005}}</ref><ref name=bmj2>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Michael|title=Why can't the Daily Mail eat humble pie over MMR?|publisher=BMJ, Vol. 331|date=12 November 2005|pmc=1283291}}</ref> Phillips continued to support Wakefield after his research methods and motives began to attract serious scrutiny and criticism: \"While Mr Wakefield is being subjected to a witch-hunt, and while the parents of the affected children are scandalously denied legal aid to pursue the court case which may well have finally brought to light the truth about MMR, those powerful people in the medical establishment are continuing to misrepresent the evidence.\"<ref>[http://www.melaniephillips.com/mmr-the-facade-cracks MMR : the facade cracks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113142000/http://www.melaniephillips.com/mmr-the-facade-cracks |date=13 November 2013 }}, published 7 February 2006, retrieved 13 November 2013.</ref> <ref>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Michael|title=The death agony of the anti-MMR campaign|url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2005/11/11/the-death-agony-of-the-anti-mmr-campaign-2/|accessdate=20 June 2019|newspaper=Spiked|date=11 November 2005}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2010, Andrew Wakefield was struck off the Medical Register for \"serious professional misconduct\", and is currently barred from practising medicine in the UK.<ref name=MeikleBoseley>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2010/may/24/mmr-doctor-andrew-wakefield-struck-off |title=MMR row doctor Andrew Wakefield struck off register |work=The Guardian|date= 24 May 2010|accessdate=24 May 2010 | location=London | last1= Meikle|first1=James|first2=Sarah|last2=Boseley| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527003931/http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2010/may/24/mmr-doctor-andrew-wakefield-struck-off| archivedate= 27 May 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Phillips's support of Wakefield's \"findings\" and her campaign against the MMR vaccine has been both widely noted,<ref name=falseprophets/><ref name=dean>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UFJSxmvYymEC&pg=PA318&dq=Tammy+Boyce+Health,+Risk+and+News&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kfaDUsblKcKrtAaF3oDYBw&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Melanie%20Phillips&f=false Malcolm Dean. ''Democracy Under Attack: How the Media Distort Policy and Politics''] The Policy Press, 2012: p. 371.</ref> and credited for significantly undermining public trust in vaccines.<ref name=falseprophets>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_epul7PlKccC&pg=PT65&lpg=PT65&dq=Melanie+Phillips+MMR+vaccine&source=bl&ots=0MqKXf5NAF&sig=qI6qOHeCyICxGpnWfrvMmFCOxWQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=APSDUuzXIKWm4AT7q4HoBA&ved=0CFgQ6AEwBjhG#v=onepage&q=Melanie%20Phillips%20MMR%20vaccine&f=false Paul A. Offit. ''Autism's False Prophets: Bad Science, Risky Medicine, and the Search for a Cure''] Columbia University Press, 2013: p.  56.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPhillips is married to [[Joshua Rozenberg]], former legal affairs editor for the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noelgay.com/html/artist_corporate.php?id=200 |title=Joshua Rozenberg |publisher=Noel Gay |accessdate=11 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719184424/http://www.noelgay.com/html/artist_corporate.php?id=200 |archivedate=19 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=NVXK4rGx9IG%2BYowDAXJhXQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=22 June 2017|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> They have two children.<ref name=\"Ashley2006\">{{cite news|last=Ashley|first=Jackie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/jun/16/media.politicsphilosophyandsociety|title=The multicultural menace, anti-semitism and me|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 June 2006|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n* ''The Divided House: Women at Westminster'', Sidgwick and Jackson, 1980, {{ISBN|0-283-98547-X}}.\n* ''Doctors' Dilemmas: Medical Ethics and Contemporary Science'' by Melanie Phillips & John Dawson, Harvester Press, 1985, {{ISBN|0-7108-0983-2}}.\n* ''All Must Have Prizes'', Warner, 1998, {{ISBN|0-7515-2274-0}}.\n* ''The Sex-Change Society: Feminised Britain and the Neutered Male'', Social Market Foundation, 1999, {{ISBN|1-874097-64-X}}.\n* ''America's Social Revolution'', Civitas: Institute for the Study of Civil Society, 2001, {{ISBN|1-903386-15-2}}.\n* ''The Ascent of Woman: A History of the Suffragette Movement and the Ideas Behind it'', Little, Brown, 2003, {{ISBN|0-316-72533-1}}.\n* ''[[Londonistan (book)|Londonistan: How Britain Is Creating a Terror State Within]]'', Gibson Square Books Ltd, 2006, {{ISBN|1-903933-76-5}}.\n* ''The World Turned Upside Down: The Global Battle Over God, Truth and Power'', New York, Encounter Books, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-59403-375-9}}.\n* ''Guardian Angel: My Story, My Britain'', emBooks, 1 edition (1 May 2013), {{ASIN|B00CMA0KP6}}\n* ''The Legacy'' (novel), Bombardier Books, 2018 {{ISBN|978-1-68261-566-9}}\n* ''Guardian Angel: My Journey from Leftism to Sanity,'' Bombardier Books, 2018.<ref name=\"TellerReview\">{{cite news |last1=Teller |first1=Neville |title=A journalist's journey The transformational autobiography of Melanie Phillips (bok review) |url=https://www.jpost.com/Jerusalem-Report/A-journalists-journey-583474 |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher=Jerusalem Report |date=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{official website|www.melaniephillips.com|Melanie Phillips}} \u2013 official site\n*{{C-SPAN|Melanie Phillips}}\n**[http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/311970-1 Melanie Phillips] ''[[In Depth]]'' interview on [[C-SPAN]], 5 May 2013\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Phillips, Melanie}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Anne's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Jews]]\n[[Category:British conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:British critics of Islam]]\n[[Category:British journalists]]\n[[Category:British radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Daily Mail journalists]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n[[Category:The Sunday Times people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Putney High School]]\n[[Category:Anti-vaccination activists]]\n[[Category:British social commentators]]\n", "name_user": "Alfie350", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClimate change:removed unnecessary information unrelated to Melanie Phillips (this is her Biography after all), and removed loaded words showing bias to ensure a neutral tone throughout.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanie_Phillips"}
{"title_page": "Frank DeCicco", "text_new": "{{Essay-like|date=October 2010}}\n{{confused|Frank DiCicco}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name                      = Frank DeCicco\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1935|11|05}}\n| birth_place               = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1986|04|13|1935|11|05}}\n| death_place               = New York City, U.S. \n| death_cause               = [[Car bomb]]\n| resting_place             = [[Moravian Cemetery]],<br>[[Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| criminal_charge           = \n| criminal_penalty          = \n| spouse                    = Rosemarie Suriani DeCicco\n| children                  = 2\n| relatives                 = [[George DeCicco]] (uncle)\n| allegiance                = [[Gambino crime family]]\n| occupation                = [[Mobster]]\n}}\n'''Frank DeCicco'''  also known as '''Frankie D''' and '''Frankie Cheech''' (November 5, 1935 \u2013 April 13, 1986) was the underboss for the [[Gambino crime family]] in [[New York City]].\n\n==Background==\nDeCicco was the son of Vincent \"Boozy\" DeCicco from [[Benevento, Italy]], an alcoholic soldier with the Gambino family. DeCicco grew up in [[Bath Beach, Brooklyn]], but lived as an adult on [[Staten Island]].\n\nFrank DeCicco's brother was Gambino soldier George DeCicco and his sister was Betty DeCicco.<ref name=\"short list\">{{cite news|last=Rashbaum|first=William K.|title=Now on the F.B.I.'s Short List: Two Men, Long Out of Sight|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/22/nyregion/now-on-the-fbi-s-short-list-two-men-long-out-of-sight.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=22 June 2002}}</ref>  Frank's uncle was Gambino capo George DeCicco.<ref name=\"last gottis\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Stephanie|title=LAST OF THE GOTTI GANG|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/regional/item_koS6kwzmieYiI0D9zBCLFK|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Post|date=January 31, 2007}}</ref><ref name=bensonhurst>{{cite news|last=Feuer|first=Alan|title=Bensonhurst Journal; In Brooklyn, a Quiet Avenue With Dirty Laundry|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/16/nyregion/bensonhurst-journal-in-brooklyn-a-quiet-avenue-with-dirty-laundry.html?scp=20&sq=DeCicco%20indictment&st=cse|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=16 April 2000}}</ref> Frank had two children, Vincent and Grace. Vincent died of lung cancer in 2008. Frank's nephew was Gambino mobster Robert DeCicco.<ref name=\"hit miss\">{{cite news|last=Weiss|first=Murray|title=MOB HIT & MISS IN BROOKLYN|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/regional/item_AcDnb67JiTEThaklYJD7cK|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Post|date=June 6, 1007}}</ref>\n\nFrank was a tall, muscular man with a thick neck that showed exposed thick arteries when he was angry. DeCicco dyed his silver hair black, leaving silver streaks styled in a [[pompadour (hairstyle)|pompadour]] quaff. He also had a slightly mashed nose. A low-profile mobster, DeCicco drove a non-descript  [[Buick_Electra#1985%E2%80%931990|1985 Buick Electra]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/14/nyregion/car-bomb-kills-the-no-2-man-in-crime-family.html The New York Time CAR BOMB KILLS THE NO. 2 MAN IN CRIME FAMILY By Peter Kerr April 14, 1986]</ref> Frank was a disorganized man who stuffed dozens of business cards in his suit jacket and kept a messy car.  Former underboss and government witness [[Sammy Gravano]] described DeCicco as being calculating and observant. Gambino boss [[Paul Castellano]] once commented on DeCicco to Gravano; \"Frankie? Frank's a gambler. He's a street dog Sammy.\" A successful gambler who played [[craps]] games or [[roulette]], DeCicco frequented many [[illegal gambling]] establishments in Brooklyn and Manhattan and owned his own social club in [[Bensonhurst, Brooklyn]].{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\n==Castellano protegee==\nIn the late 1960s to early 1970s, DeCicco joined the Gambino family and soon became a \"soldier\". In 1973, DeCicco and future [[Lucchese crime family]] underboss [[Anthony Casso]] were robbing diamond dealers and hijacking trucks throughout New York State. DeCicco eventually became a protegee of boss Paul Castellano, also a Bath Beach native.  DeCicco was also close to Gambino capo [[James Failla]], whom he described as his \"[[rabbi]]\". DeCicco's crew was one of the most powerful in the Gambino family. It included associate [[Joe Watts | Joseph Watts]], [[John Gotti]]'s chauffeur and bodyguard, Joseph Paruta, and Vito Rizzuto Sr.\n\nDeCicco became heavily involved in labor [[racketeering]] with the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] Union Local 282. Through Castellano, he held a no-show [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] union official position with the Local 282.  The members of Local 282 delivered concrete and building materials to construction sites in New York City and Long Island. Although paid overtime, DeCicco was rarely present at any construction sites. DeCicco installed many Gambino members into the Local and was responsible for delivering payoffs from union bosses to the Gambino administration.  DeCicco often attended meetings at Castellano's [[Todt Hill, Staten Island]] mansion.\n\n==Scibetta and DeMeo murders==\nIn 1978, Castellano allegedly ordered the murder of Gambino associate [[Nicholas Scibetta]]. A [[cocaine]] and [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] user, Scibetta participated in several public fights and insulted the daughter of [[George DeCicco]]. Since Scibetta was [[Salvatore \"Sammy the Bull\" Gravano]]'s brother-in-law, Castellano asked Frank to first notify Gravano of the impending hit. When advised of Scibetta's fate, a furious Gravano said he would kill Castellano first. However, Gravano was eventually calmed by DeCicco and accepted Scibetta's death as the punishment earned by his behavior.<ref name=sci>{{cite web|last=May|first=Allan|title=Living by the Rules|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/mob_bosses/gravano/rules_7.html|work=Sammy \"The Bull\" Gravano|publisher=Crime Library|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, Castellano ordered DeCicco to arrange the murder of Gambino soldier [[Roy DeMeo]]. DeMeo headed a crew that had committed as many as 200 contract killings. By 1983, DeMeo was under heavy law enforcement investigation. Worried that DeMeo might become a government witness, Castellano ordered his killing. Given DeMeo's fearsome reputation, DeCicco found it difficult to find any family members who would take the job. Finally, DeCicco recruited Gambino associates [[Anthony Senter]] and [[Joseph Testa]], both members of DeMeo's crew, to murder their capo.  The two mobsters murdered DeMeo on January 10, 1983.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\n==Castellano and Bilotti murders==\nIn late 1985, DeCicco and [[John Gotti]]<!-- Sr.--> conspired to murder Castellano and his new underboss, [[Thomas Bilotti]]. Castellano had enraged many traditional family members with his fixation on [[White-collar crime|white collar]] crime and his perceived stinginess. When Castellano appointed his chauffeur Bilotti as underboss to replace the recently deceased {{nowrap|[[Aniello Dellacroce]],<ref name=tplvd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CtxVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DeEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5927%2C712063 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |title='Top level hoodlum' dies of cancer |date=December 4, 1985 |page=12A}}</ref>}} Gotti decided to move against Castellano. Although DeCicco had enjoyed close ties with Castellano, he joined Gotti, [[Joseph Armone]], Gravano, and [[Frank Locascio]] in the murder conspiracy. DeCicco tipped Gotti off that he would be having a meeting with Castellano and several other Gambino mobsters at Sparks Steak House on December 16. DeCicco and mobster James Failla appealed to Castellano to meet with the son of Dellacroce. Since Castellano had skipped Dellacroce's [[Wake (ceremony)|wake]], this was a good way to make amends to the family. The dinner meeting was set for [[Sparks Steak House]] in {{nowrap|[[Midtown Manhattan]].<ref name=\"new godfather\">{{cite news|last=Daly|first=Michael|title=The New Godfather: The Rise of John Gotti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mucCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38|accessdate=7 December 2011|newspaper=New York Magazine|date=June 23, 1986}}</ref>}}\n\nJust before 5:30 p.m. on Monday, December 16, Castellano and Bilotti were [[Paul Castellano#Assassination|shot to death]] while exiting their [[Lincoln Town Car]] outside of {{nowrap|Sparks Steak House.<ref name=ergaprmb>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-ttVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DeEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3061%2C4363821 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |title=Reputed Mafia boss murdered |date=December 17, 1985 |page=3A}}</ref><ref name=sraphit>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=0klj8wIChNAC&dat=19851217&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=(''New York Daily News'') |title=Crime boss, bodyguard murdered in Manhattan |date=December 17, 1985 |page=A1}}</ref><ref name=upimbbmlbl>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=62APAAAAIBAJ&sjid=soYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6746%2C3158237 |work=The Bulletin |location=(Bend, Oregon) |agency=UPI |title=Mob boss murder leads to bulletin for Lincoln car |date=December 17, 1985 |page=D4}}</ref><ref name=\"manhattan brooklyn\">{{cite web|last=Bruno|first=Anthony|title=The Gambino Crime Family: Manhattan vs. Brooklyn|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/4.html|work=TruTV Crime Library|accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>}}\n\nSoon after Castellano's death, Gotti declared himself the new family boss and designated DeCicco as his underboss.  DeCicco took control of all of the \"[[White-collar crime|white collar]]\" rackets that once belonged to the Castellano faction. Prior to the two murders, Gravano told DeCicco that he, not Gotti, should become the new boss with Gotti as underboss.  DeCicco replied to Gravano,\n\n<blockquote>John's fucking ego is too big. I could be his underboss, but he couldn't be mine. Look, he's got balls, he's got brains, he's got charisma. If we can control him to stop the gambling and all of his flamboyant bullshit, he could be a good boss. Sammy, I'll tell you what. We'll give him a shot. Let him be the boss. If it don't work within a year, me and you, we'll kill him. I'll become the boss, and you'll be my underboss, and we'll run the family right.<ref>{{cite book|last=Maas|first=Peter|title=Underboss: Sammy the Bull Gravano's Story of Life in the Mafia|url=https://archive.org/details/underbosssammyb000maas|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=HarperPaperbacks|location=New York, N.Y.|isbn=0-06-109664-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/underbosssammyb000maas/page/n343 314]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nGravano would later say in his autobiography, \"Louie (Milito) had got pinched for something and was away for a short time when we made our move (the murders of Paul Castellano and Thomas Bilotti.) Frankie was steaming. Louie could have betrayed us if he wasn't in jail. He was playing both sides. As soon as Louie got out of jail, Frankie said he had to be killed. A guy like that was too devious. I argued for Louie's life. I asked Frankie, who was now our underboss, to let Louie come under me (Gravano's supervision). After all, we had spared people before. I would tell Louie what we discovered. I would put him on the shelf. I tried to convince Frankie that we didn't have to kill him. But Frankie was adamant. Louie had to die.\"\n\n==Death==\n\nOn April 13, 1986, DeCicco was killed in [[Dyker Heights, Brooklyn]], when his car was [[car bomb|bombed]] following a visit to Castellano loyalist [[James Failla]]. The bombing was carried out by [[Victor Amuso]] and [[Anthony Casso]] of the Lucchese family, under orders of [[Vincent Gigante]] and Lucchese boss [[Anthony Corallo]], to avenge Castellano and Bilotti by killing their successors; Gotti also planned to visit Failla that day, but canceled, and the bomb was detonated after a soldier who rode with DeCicco was mistaken for the boss.<ref name=\"raab 473\">Raab, pp. 473\u2013476</ref><ref name=\"last don\">{{cite web|last=Bruno|first=Anthony|title=The Gambino Crime Family:The Last Don|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/5.html|work=TruTV Crime Library|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1997, author [[Jerry Capeci]] reported that Casso, now a government witness, revealed that the plotters selected Genovese associate Herbert Pate to kill Gotti with an [[improvised explosive device]] (IED).  Casso told investigators that the plotters decided to kill Gotti and DeCicco with a bomb in order to make the Gambinos think that [[Zips]], or Sicilian mafiosi, were involved. Although Sicilian gangsters are notorious for using bombs, they have long been forbidden in the American Mafia since they put innocent people at risk. Casso also told authorities that Pate was selected because he had no links to the Gambino family and thus would not be recognized while staking out DeCicco.<ref name=\"secret up\">{{cite news|last=Capeci|first=Jerry|title=SECRET'S UP IN SLAY OF GOTTI CONFIDANT|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/secret-slay-gotti-confidant-article-1.785735|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 12, 1997}}</ref><ref>Capeci, Mustain (1996), pp. 139\u2013140</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nSupervising agent for the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA), Edward Magnuson testified that a confidential informant had told him that Gotti was, \"very angry relative to the murder of Frank DeCicco, and when he was out on bail, or when the trial was over, there was going to be a war, and John would take his revenge.\" Gotti instructed all the Gambino [[made men]] and associates to attend DeCicco's wake, held over two days at a funeral home near the bombing site. To replace DeCicco, Gotti ultimately appointed capo [[Joseph Armone]] as underboss.<ref>Maas, p. 382</ref>\n\nThe [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brooklyn]] denied DeCicco a [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] before the burial, saying it should be delayed for the sake of the DeCicco family and to honor \"the solemnity of the occasion\".<ref name=\"diocese prohibits\">{{cite news|last=Kerr|first=Peter|title=DIOCESE PROHIBITS MASS AT MOB FIGURE'S BURIAL|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/17/nyregion/diocese-prohibits-mass-at-mob-figure-s-burial.html?scp=4&sq=%22Frank%20DeCicco%22&st=cse|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=April 17, 1986}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n*In the 1996 TV film ''[[Gotti (1996 film)|Gotti]]'', Frank DeCicco is portrayed by [[Robert Miranda]].\n*In the 1998 TV film ''[[Witness to the Mob]]'', Frank is portrayed by [[Frank Vincent]].\n*In the 2018 film ''[[Gotti (2018 film)|Gotti]]'', Frank DeCicco is portrayed by [[Chris Mulkey]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Find a Grave|23291}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[American Mafia]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thomas Bilotti]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Gambino crime family]]<br />Underboss|years=1985-1986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joseph Armone]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Gambino crime family}}{{American Mafia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Decicco, Frank}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bath Beach, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Gambino crime family]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Murdered American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:People murdered by the Lucchese crime family]]\n[[Category:Deaths by improvised explosive device in the United States]]\n[[Category:People murdered in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Essay-like|date=October 2010}}\n{{confused|Frank DiCicco}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name                      = Frank DeCicco\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1935|11|05}}\n| birth_place               = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1986|04|13|1935|11|05}}\n| death_place               = New York City, U.S. \n| death_cause               = [[Car bomb]]\n| resting_place             = [[Moravian Cemetery]],<br>[[Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| criminal_charge           = \n| criminal_penalty          = \n| spouse                    = Rosemarie Suriani DeCicco\n| children                  = 2\n| relatives                 = [[George DeCicco]] (uncle)\n| allegiance                = [[Gambino crime family]]\n| occupation                = [[Mobster]]\n}}\n'''Frank DeCicco'''  also known as '''Frankie D''' and '''Frankie Cheech''' (November 5, 1935 \u2013 April 13, 1986) was the underboss for the [[Gambino crime family]] in [[New York City]].\n\n==Background==\nDeCicco was the son of Vincent \"Boozy\" DeCicco from [[Benevento, Italy]], an alcoholic soldier with the Gambino family. DeCicco grew up in [[Bath Beach, Brooklyn]], but lived as an adult on [[Staten Island]].\n\nFrank DeCicco's brother was Gambino soldier George DeCicco and his sister was Betty DeCicco.<ref name=\"short list\">{{cite news|last=Rashbaum|first=William K.|title=Now on the F.B.I.'s Short List: Two Men, Long Out of Sight|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/22/nyregion/now-on-the-fbi-s-short-list-two-men-long-out-of-sight.html|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=22 June 2002}}</ref>  Frank's uncle was Gambino capo George DeCicco.<ref name=\"last gottis\">{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Stephanie|title=LAST OF THE GOTTI GANG|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/regional/item_koS6kwzmieYiI0D9zBCLFK|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Post|date=January 31, 2007}}</ref><ref name=bensonhurst>{{cite news|last=Feuer|first=Alan|title=Bensonhurst Journal; In Brooklyn, a Quiet Avenue With Dirty Laundry|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/16/nyregion/bensonhurst-journal-in-brooklyn-a-quiet-avenue-with-dirty-laundry.html?scp=20&sq=DeCicco%20indictment&st=cse|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=16 April 2000}}</ref> Frank had two children, Vincent and Grace. Vincent died of lung cancer in 2008. Frank's nephew was Gambino mobster Robert DeCicco.<ref name=\"hit miss\">{{cite news|last=Weiss|first=Murray|title=MOB HIT & MISS IN BROOKLYN|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/regional/item_AcDnb67JiTEThaklYJD7cK|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Post|date=June 6, 1007}}</ref>\n\nFrank was a tall, muscular man with a thick neck that showed exposed thick arteries when he was angry. DeCicco dyed his silver hair black, leaving silver streaks styled in a [[pompadour (hairstyle)|pompadour]] quaff. He also had a slightly mashed nose. A low-profile mobster, DeCicco drove a non-descript  [[Buick_Electra#1985%E2%80%931990|1985 Buick Electra]]<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/14/nyregion/car-bomb-kills-the-no-2-man-in-crime-family.html The New York Time CAR BOMB KILLS THE NO. 2 MAN IN CRIME FAMILY By Peter Kerr April 14, 1986]</ref>. Frank was a disorganized man who stuffed dozens of business cards in his suit jacket and kept a messy car.  Former underboss and government witness [[Sammy Gravano]] described DeCicco as being calculating and observant. Gambino boss [[Paul Castellano]] once commented on DeCicco to Gravano; \"Frankie? Frank's a gambler. He's a street dog Sammy.\" A successful gambler who played [[craps]] games or [[roulette]], DeCicco frequented many [[illegal gambling]] establishments in Brooklyn and Manhattan and owned his own social club in [[Bensonhurst, Brooklyn]].{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\n==Castellano protegee==\nIn the late 1960s to early 1970s, DeCicco joined the Gambino family and soon became a \"soldier\". In 1973, DeCicco and future [[Lucchese crime family]] underboss [[Anthony Casso]] were robbing diamond dealers and hijacking trucks throughout New York State. DeCicco eventually became a protegee of boss Paul Castellano, also a Bath Beach native.  DeCicco was also close to Gambino capo [[James Failla]], whom he described as his \"[[rabbi]]\". DeCicco's crew was one of the most powerful in the Gambino family. It included associate [[Joe Watts | Joseph Watts]], [[John Gotti]]'s chauffeur and bodyguard, Joseph Paruta, and Vito Rizzuto Sr.\n\nDeCicco became heavily involved in labor [[racketeering]] with the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] Union Local 282. Through Castellano, he held a no-show [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters]] union official position with the Local 282.  The members of Local 282 delivered concrete and building materials to construction sites in New York City and Long Island. Although paid overtime, DeCicco was rarely present at any construction sites. DeCicco installed many Gambino members into the Local and was responsible for delivering payoffs from union bosses to the Gambino administration.  DeCicco often attended meetings at Castellano's [[Todt Hill, Staten Island]] mansion.\n\n==Scibetta and DeMeo murders==\nIn 1978, Castellano allegedly ordered the murder of Gambino associate [[Nicholas Scibetta]]. A [[cocaine]] and [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] user, Scibetta participated in several public fights and insulted the daughter of [[George DeCicco]]. Since Scibetta was [[Salvatore \"Sammy the Bull\" Gravano]]'s brother-in-law, Castellano asked Frank to first notify Gravano of the impending hit. When advised of Scibetta's fate, a furious Gravano said he would kill Castellano first. However, Gravano was eventually calmed by DeCicco and accepted Scibetta's death as the punishment earned by his behavior.<ref name=sci>{{cite web|last=May|first=Allan|title=Living by the Rules|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/mob_bosses/gravano/rules_7.html|work=Sammy \"The Bull\" Gravano|publisher=Crime Library|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, Castellano ordered DeCicco to arrange the murder of Gambino soldier [[Roy DeMeo]]. DeMeo headed a crew that had committed as many as 200 contract killings. By 1983, DeMeo was under heavy law enforcement investigation. Worried that DeMeo might become a government witness, Castellano ordered his killing. Given DeMeo's fearsome reputation, DeCicco found it difficult to find any family members who would take the job. Finally, DeCicco recruited Gambino associates [[Anthony Senter]] and [[Joseph Testa]], both members of DeMeo's crew, to murder their capo.  The two mobsters murdered DeMeo on January 10, 1983.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\n==Castellano and Bilotti murders==\nIn late 1985, DeCicco and [[John Gotti]]<!-- Sr.--> conspired to murder Castellano and his new underboss, [[Thomas Bilotti]]. Castellano had enraged many traditional family members with his fixation on [[White-collar crime|white collar]] crime and his perceived stinginess. When Castellano appointed his chauffeur Bilotti as underboss to replace the recently deceased {{nowrap|[[Aniello Dellacroce]],<ref name=tplvd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CtxVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DeEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5927%2C712063 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |title='Top level hoodlum' dies of cancer |date=December 4, 1985 |page=12A}}</ref>}} Gotti decided to move against Castellano. Although DeCicco had enjoyed close ties with Castellano, he joined Gotti, [[Joseph Armone]], Gravano, and [[Frank Locascio]] in the murder conspiracy. DeCicco tipped Gotti off that he would be having a meeting with Castellano and several other Gambino mobsters at Sparks Steak House on December 16. DeCicco and mobster James Failla appealed to Castellano to meet with the son of Dellacroce. Since Castellano had skipped Dellacroce's [[Wake (ceremony)|wake]], this was a good way to make amends to the family. The dinner meeting was set for [[Sparks Steak House]] in {{nowrap|[[Midtown Manhattan]].<ref name=\"new godfather\">{{cite news|last=Daly|first=Michael|title=The New Godfather: The Rise of John Gotti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mucCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38|accessdate=7 December 2011|newspaper=New York Magazine|date=June 23, 1986}}</ref>}}\n\nJust before 5:30 p.m. on Monday, December 16, Castellano and Bilotti were [[Paul Castellano#Assassination|shot to death]] while exiting their [[Lincoln Town Car]] outside of {{nowrap|Sparks Steak House.<ref name=ergaprmb>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-ttVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DeEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3061%2C4363821 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |title=Reputed Mafia boss murdered |date=December 17, 1985 |page=3A}}</ref><ref name=sraphit>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=0klj8wIChNAC&dat=19851217&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=(''New York Daily News'') |title=Crime boss, bodyguard murdered in Manhattan |date=December 17, 1985 |page=A1}}</ref><ref name=upimbbmlbl>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=62APAAAAIBAJ&sjid=soYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6746%2C3158237 |work=The Bulletin |location=(Bend, Oregon) |agency=UPI |title=Mob boss murder leads to bulletin for Lincoln car |date=December 17, 1985 |page=D4}}</ref><ref name=\"manhattan brooklyn\">{{cite web|last=Bruno|first=Anthony|title=The Gambino Crime Family: Manhattan vs. Brooklyn|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/4.html|work=TruTV Crime Library|accessdate=7 December 2011}}</ref>}}\n\nSoon after Castellano's death, Gotti declared himself the new family boss and designated DeCicco as his underboss.  DeCicco took control of all of the \"[[White-collar crime|white collar]]\" rackets that once belonged to the Castellano faction. Prior to the two murders, Gravano told DeCicco that he, not Gotti, should become the new boss with Gotti as underboss.  DeCicco replied to Gravano,\n\n<blockquote>John's fucking ego is too big. I could be his underboss, but he couldn't be mine. Look, he's got balls, he's got brains, he's got charisma. If we can control him to stop the gambling and all of his flamboyant bullshit, he could be a good boss. Sammy, I'll tell you what. We'll give him a shot. Let him be the boss. If it don't work within a year, me and you, we'll kill him. I'll become the boss, and you'll be my underboss, and we'll run the family right.<ref>{{cite book|last=Maas|first=Peter|title=Underboss: Sammy the Bull Gravano's Story of Life in the Mafia|url=https://archive.org/details/underbosssammyb000maas|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=HarperPaperbacks|location=New York, N.Y.|isbn=0-06-109664-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/underbosssammyb000maas/page/n343 314]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nGravano would later say in his autobiography, \"Louie (Milito) had got pinched for something and was away for a short time when we made our move (the murders of Paul Castellano and Thomas Bilotti.) Frankie was steaming. Louie could have betrayed us if he wasn't in jail. He was playing both sides. As soon as Louie got out of jail, Frankie said he had to be killed. A guy like that was too devious. I argued for Louie's life. I asked Frankie, who was now our underboss, to let Louie come under me (Gravano's supervision). After all, we had spared people before. I would tell Louie what we discovered. I would put him on the shelf. I tried to convince Frankie that we didn't have to kill him. But Frankie was adamant. Louie had to die.\"\n\n==Death==\n\nOn April 13, 1986, DeCicco was killed in [[Dyker Heights, Brooklyn]], when his car was [[car bomb|bombed]] following a visit to Castellano loyalist [[James Failla]]. The bombing was carried out by [[Victor Amuso]] and [[Anthony Casso]] of the Lucchese family, under orders of [[Vincent Gigante]] and Lucchese boss [[Anthony Corallo]], to avenge Castellano and Bilotti by killing their successors; Gotti also planned to visit Failla that day, but canceled, and the bomb was detonated after a soldier who rode with DeCicco was mistaken for the boss.<ref name=\"raab 473\">Raab, pp. 473\u2013476</ref><ref name=\"last don\">{{cite web|last=Bruno|first=Anthony|title=The Gambino Crime Family:The Last Don|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/5.html|work=TruTV Crime Library|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1997, author [[Jerry Capeci]] reported that Casso, now a government witness, revealed that the plotters selected Genovese associate Herbert Pate to kill Gotti with an [[improvised explosive device]] (IED).  Casso told investigators that the plotters decided to kill Gotti and DeCicco with a bomb in order to make the Gambinos think that [[Zips]], or Sicilian mafiosi, were involved. Although Sicilian gangsters are notorious for using bombs, they have long been forbidden in the American Mafia since they put innocent people at risk. Casso also told authorities that Pate was selected because he had no links to the Gambino family and thus would not be recognized while staking out DeCicco.<ref name=\"secret up\">{{cite news|last=Capeci|first=Jerry|title=SECRET'S UP IN SLAY OF GOTTI CONFIDANT|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/secret-slay-gotti-confidant-article-1.785735|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 12, 1997}}</ref><ref>Capeci, Mustain (1996), pp. 139\u2013140</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nSupervising agent for the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA), Edward Magnuson testified that a confidential informant had told him that Gotti was, \"very angry relative to the murder of Frank DeCicco, and when he was out on bail, or when the trial was over, there was going to be a war, and John would take his revenge.\" Gotti instructed all the Gambino [[made men]] and associates to attend DeCicco's wake, held over two days at a funeral home near the bombing site. To replace DeCicco, Gotti ultimately appointed capo [[Joseph Armone]] as underboss.<ref>Maas, p. 382</ref>\n\nThe [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brooklyn]] denied DeCicco a [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] before the burial, saying it should be delayed for the sake of the DeCicco family and to honor \"the solemnity of the occasion\".<ref name=\"diocese prohibits\">{{cite news|last=Kerr|first=Peter|title=DIOCESE PROHIBITS MASS AT MOB FIGURE'S BURIAL|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/17/nyregion/diocese-prohibits-mass-at-mob-figure-s-burial.html?scp=4&sq=%22Frank%20DeCicco%22&st=cse|accessdate=6 December 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=April 17, 1986}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n*In the 1996 TV film ''[[Gotti (1996 film)|Gotti]]'', Frank DeCicco is portrayed by [[Robert Miranda]].\n*In the 1998 TV film ''[[Witness to the Mob]]'', Frank is portrayed by [[Frank Vincent]].\n*In the 2018 film ''[[Gotti (2018 film)|Gotti]]'', Frank DeCicco is portrayed by [[Chris Mulkey]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Find a Grave|23291}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[American Mafia]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thomas Bilotti]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Gambino crime family]]<br />Underboss|years=1985-1986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joseph Armone]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Gambino crime family}}{{American Mafia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Decicco, Frank}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bath Beach, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Gambino crime family]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Murdered American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n[[Category:People murdered by the Lucchese crime family]]\n[[Category:Deaths by improvised explosive device in the United States]]\n[[Category:People murdered in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": 