{"title_page": "Frank Carideo", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Frank Carideo\n| image = Frank Carideo.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1908|8|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Mount Vernon, New York]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1992|3|17|1908|8|4}}\n| death_place = [[Ocean Springs, Mississippi]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1928\u20131930\n| player_team2 = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| player_positions = [[Quarterback]]\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1931\n| coach_team2 = [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1932\u20131934\n| coach_team3 = [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]]\n| coach_years4 = 1935\u20131938\n| coach_team4 = [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] (assistant)\n| coach_years5 = 1939\u20131942\n| coach_team5 = [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]] (assistant)\n| coach_years6 = 1946\u20131949\n| coach_team6 = [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]] (assistant)\n| coach_sport7 = Basketball\n| coach_years8 = 1935\u20131939\n| coach_team8 = [[Mississippi State Bulldogs men's basketball|Mississippi State]]\n| overall_record = 2\u201323\u20132 (football)<br>43\u201339 (basketball)\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = [[1929 College Football All-America Team|All-American, 1929]]<br>[[1930 College Football All-America Team|All-American, 1930]]\n| coaching_records = \n| CFBHOF_year = 1954\n| CFBHOF_id = 1370\n}}\n'''Francis F. Carideo''' (August 4, 1908 \u2013 March 17, 1992) was an [[American football]] player and coach of football and basketball.  He played [[quarterback]] at the [[University of Notre Dame]] from 1928 to 1930, where he was a two-time [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]].  Carideo served as the head football coach at the [[University of Missouri]] from 1932 to 1934, compiling a record of 2\u201323\u20132.  He was also the head basketball coach at [[Mississippi State University]] from 1935 to 1939, tallying a mark of 43\u201339.  Carideo was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] as a player in 1954.\n\n==Biography==\nCarideo was born in [[Mount Vernon, New York]].  He attended the [[University of Notre Dame]] in [[South Bend, Indiana]], where he played quarterback for coach [[Knute Rockne]]'s [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football]] team from 1928 to 1930. As a college football player he was considered so good, that even Rockne said he was the best quarterback ever.  During the 1929 and 1930 seasons, the Fighting Irish posted a perfect 19\u20130 record with him as the starter, and he is remembered as a \"big play maker.\"\n\nCarideo was also an assistant coach at [[Purdue University|Purdue]] in 1931, at [[Mississippi State University|Mississippi State]] from 1935 to 1938, and at [[University of Iowa|Iowa]] from 1939 to 1942 and 1946 to 1949.\n\nIn July of 1931, he became engaged to Vera Imogene Crawley of Columbia, Mississippi.<ref>http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,742023,00.html</ref> They were married on November 23 in the Administration Building at Notre Dame.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1931/11/24/archives/frank-carideo-marries-former-notre-dame-football-star-weds-miss.html</ref>\n\nCarideo died in [[Ocean Springs, Mississippi]] in 1992; he was 83 years old.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===Football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri Tigers]]\n | conf      = [[Big Eight Conference|Big Six Conference]]\n | startyear = 1932\n | endyear   = 1934\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1932 college football season|1932]]\n | name         = [[1932 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]]\n | overall      = 1\u20137\u20131\n | conference   = 1\u20133\u20131\n | confstanding = 5th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1933 college football season|1933]]\n | name         = [[1933 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]]\n | overall      = 1\u20138\n | conference   = 0\u20135\n | confstanding = 6th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1934 college football season|1934]]\n | name         = [[1934 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]]\n | overall      = 0\u20138\u20131\n | conference   = 0\u20135\n | confstanding = 6th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Missouri\n | overall    = 2\u201323\u20132\n | confrecord = 1\u201313\u20131\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 2\u201323\u20132\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nina Quartero]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cfbhof|id=1370|name=Frank Carideo}}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Navboxes| list1 =\n{{Notre Dame Fighting Irish quarterback navbox}}\n{{Missouri Tigers football coach navbox}}\n{{Mississippi State Bulldogs basketball coach navbox}}\n{{1929 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football navbox}}\n{{1930 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football navbox}}\n{{1929 College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{1930 College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carideo, Frank}}\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Iowa Hawkeyes football coaches]]\n[[Category:Mississippi State Bulldogs football coaches]]\n[[Category:Mississippi State Bulldogs men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Missouri Tigers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football players]]\n[[Category:Purdue Boilermakers football coaches]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:College Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mount Vernon, New York]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Educators from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Frank Carideo\n| image = Frank Carideo.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1908|8|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Mount Vernon, New York]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1992|3|17|1908|8|4}}\n| death_place = [[Ocean Springs, Mississippi]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1928\u20131930\n| player_team2 = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| player_positions = [[Quarterback]]\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1931\n| coach_team2 = [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1932\u20131934\n| coach_team3 = [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]]\n| coach_years4 = 1935\u20131938\n| coach_team4 = [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] (assistant)\n| coach_years5 = 1939\u20131942\n| coach_team5 = [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]] (assistant)\n| coach_years6 = 1946\u20131949\n| coach_team6 = [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]] (assistant)\n| coach_sport7 = Basketball\n| coach_years8 = 1935\u20131939\n| coach_team8 = [[Mississippi State Bulldogs men's basketball|Mississippi State]]\n| overall_record = 2\u201323\u20132 (football)<br>43\u201339 (basketball)\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = [[1929 College Football All-America Team|All-American, 1929]]<br>[[1930 College Football All-America Team|All-American, 1930]]\n| coaching_records = \n| CFBHOF_year = 1954\n| CFBHOF_id = 1370\n}}\n'''Francis F. Carideo''' (August 4, 1908 \u2013 March 17, 1992) was an [[American football]] player and coach of football and basketball.  He played [[quarterback]] at the [[University of Notre Dame]] from 1928 to 1930, where he was a two-time [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]].  Carideo served as the head football coach at the [[University of Missouri]] from 1932 to 1934, compiling a record of 2\u201323\u20132.  He was also the head basketball coach at [[Mississippi State University]] from 1935 to 1939, tallying a mark of 43\u201339.  Carideo was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] as a player in 1954.\n\n==Biography==\nCarideo was born in [[Mount Vernon, New York]].  He attended the [[University of Notre Dame]] in [[South Bend, Indiana]], where he played quarterback for coach [[Knute Rockne]]'s [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football]] team from 1928 to 1930. As a college football player he was considered so good, that even Rockne said he was the best quarterback ever.  During the 1929 and 1930 seasons, the Fighting Irish posted a perfect 19\u20130 record with him as the starter, and he is remembered as a \"big play maker.\"\n\nCarideo was also an assistant coach at [[Purdue University|Purdue]] in 1931, at [[Mississippi State University|Mississippi State]] from 1935 to 1938, and at [[University of Iowa|Iowa]] from 1939 to 1942 and 1946 to 1949.\n\nIn July of 1931, he became engaged to Vera Imogene Crawley of Columbia, Mississippi<ref>http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,742023,00.html</ref>. They were married on November 23 in the Administration Building at Notre Dame<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1931/11/24/archives/frank-carideo-marries-former-notre-dame-football-star-weds-miss.html</ref>.\n\nCarideo died in [[Ocean Springs, Mississippi]] in 1992; he was 83 years old.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===Football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Missouri Tigers fo